# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: energy-consumption
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] The term high-altitude wind power (HAWP) has been used to refer to AWE systems.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] However, semantically HAWP might also include wind energy conversion systems that are somehow positioned at a large height from the ground or sea surface.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Various mechanisms are proposed for capturing the kinetic energy of winds such as kites, kytoons, aerostats, gliders, gliders with turbines for regenerative soaring, sailplanes with turbines, or other airfoils, including multiple-point building- or terrain-enabled holdings.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Once the mechanical energy is derived from the wind's kinetic energy, then many options are available for using that mechanical energy: direct traction, conversion to electricity aloft or at ground station, conversion to laser or microwave for power beaming to other aircraft or ground receivers.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Winds at higher altitudes become steadier, more persistent, and of higher velocity.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Because power available in wind increases as the cube of velocity (the velocity-cubed law), assuming other parameters remaining the same, doubling a wind's velocity gives 23=8 times the power; tripling the velocity gives 33=27 times the available power.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] With steadier and more predictable winds, high-altitude wind has an advantage over wind near the ground.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Being able to locate HAWP to effective altitudes and using the vertical dimension of airspace for wind farming brings further advantage using high-altitude winds for generating energy.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] High-altitude wind generators can be adjusted in height and position to maximize energy return, which is impractical with fixed tower-mounted wind generators.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] In each range of altitudes there are altitude-specific concerns being addressed by researchers and developers.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] As altitude increases, tethers increase in length, the temperature of the air changes, and vulnerability to atmospheric lightning changes.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] With increasing altitude, exposure to liabilities increase, costs increase, turbulence exposure changes, likelihood of having the system fly in more than one directional strata of winds increases, and the costs of operation changes.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] HAWP systems that are flown must climb through all intermediate altitudes up to final working altitudes—being at first a low- and then a high- altitude device.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] An atlas of the high-altitude wind power resource has been prepared for all points on Earth.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] A similar atlas of global assessment was developed at Joby Energy.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] When a scheme's purpose is to propel ships and boats, the objects tether-placed in the wind will tend to have most of the captured energy be in useful tension in the main tether.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] The aloft working bodies will be operated to maintain useful tension even while the ship is moving.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] This is the method for powerkiting sports.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] This sector of HAWP is the most installed method.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Folklore suggests that Benjamin Franklin used the traction method of HAWP.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] George Pocock was a pioneer in tugging vehicles by traction.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Solutions in built systems have control mechanisms variously situated.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Some systems are passive, or active, or a mix.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] When a kite steering unit (KSU) is lofted, the KSU may be robotic and self-contained; a KSU may be operated from the ground via radio-control by a live human operator or by smart computer programs.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Some systems have built sensors in the aircraft body that report parameters like position, relative position to other parts.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Kite control units (KCU) have involved more than steering; tether reeling speeds and directions can be adjusted in response to tether tensions and needs of the system during a power-generating phase or return-non-power-generating phase.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] The mechanical energy of the device may be converted to heat, sound, electricity, light, tension, pushes, pulls, laser, microwave, chemical changes, or compression of gases.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Traction is a big direct use of the mechanical energy as in tugging cargo ships and kiteboarders.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] There are several methods of getting the mechanical energy from the wind's kinetic energy.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Lighter-than-air (LTA) moored aerostats are employed as lifters of turbines.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Heavier-than-air (HTA) tethered airfoils are being used as lifters or turbines themselves.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Combinations of LTA and HTA devices in one system are being built and flown to capture HAWP.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Even a family of free-flight airborne devices are represented in the literature that capture the kinetic energy of high-altitude winds (beginning with a description in 1967 by Richard Miller in his book *Without Visible Means of Support*) and a contemporary patent application by Dale C.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Kramer, soaring sailplane competitor, inventor.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] A research on airborne wind turbine technology innovations reveals that the “Kite type AWTs” technique, the most common type, has high scope of growth in the future; it has contributed for about 44% of the total airborne wind energy during 2008–2012.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] The kite type AWTs extract energy through wind turbines suspended at high altitudes using kites such as multi-tethered kite, kite and dual purpose circular fan, rotary wing kites etc.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Electricity generation is just one of the options for capturing mechanical energy; however, this option dominates the focus of professionals aiming to supply large amounts of energy to commerce and utilities.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] A long array of secondary options include tugging water turbines, pumping of water, or compressing air or hydrogen.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] The position of the electric generator is a distinguishing feature among systems.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Flying the generator aloft is done in a variety of ways.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Keeping the generator at the mooring region is another large design option.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] The option in one system of a generator aloft and at the ground station has been used where a small generator operates electronic devices aloft while the ground generator is the big worker to make electricity for significant loads.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] The “Carousel” configuration several kites fly at a constant height and higher altitudes, pulling in rotation a generator that moves on a wide circular rail.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] For a large Carousel system, the power obtained can be calculated as of the order of GW, exposing a law that see the power attainable as a function of the diameter raised to the fifth power, while the increment of cost of the generator is linear.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] One method of keeping working HAWP systems aloft is to use buoyant aerostats whether or not the electric generator is lifted or left on the ground.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] The aerostats are usually, but not always, shaped to achieve a kiting lifting effect.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Recharging leaked lifting gas receives various solutions.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] In case of productive winds the aerostats are typically blown down by the aerodynamic drag applied on the wide and unavoidable Reynolds surface excluding them de facto from the HAWP category.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Conceptually, two adjacent mountains (natural or terrain-enabled) or artificial buildings or towers (urban or artificial) could have a wind turbine suspended between them by use of cables.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] When HAWP is cabled between two mountain tops across a valley, the HAWP device is not airborne, but borne up by the cable system.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] No such systems are known to be in use, though patents teach these methods.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] When non-cabled bridges are the foundation for holding wind turbines high above the ground, then these are grouped with conventional towered turbines and are outside the intent of HAWP where the tethering an airborne system is foundational.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Lightning, aircraft traffic, emergency procedures, system inspections, visibility marking of system parts and its tethers, electrical safety, runaway-wing procedures, over-powering controls, appropriate mooring, and more form the safety environment for HAWP systems.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] There have been several periods of high interest in HAWP before the contemporary activity.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] The first period had a high focus on pulling carriages over the lands and capturing atmospheric electricity and lightning for human use.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] The second period was in the 1970s and 1980s when research and investment flourished; a drop in oil price resulted in no significant installations of HAWP.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Return on investment (ROI) has been the key parameter; that ROI remains in focus in the current development activity while in the background is the renewable and sustainable energy movement supporting wind power of any kind; but HAWP must compete on ROI with conventional towered solutions.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] A test center at Lista, Norway provides independent verification of research.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Early centuries of kiting demonstrated that the kite is a rotary engine that rotates its tether part about its mooring point and causes hands and arms to move because of the energy captured from higher winds into the mechanical device.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] The tension in the lofted devices performs the work of lifting and pulling body parts and things.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Airborne wind energy (AWE) for HAWP was birthed thousands of years ago; naming what happened and developing the implied potentials of tethered aircraft for doing special works is what is occurring in AWE HAWP.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] What is "low" for some workers is "high" for others.
[src:energy-consumption/airborne-wind-energy] Autorotation is the basis of a large sector of AWE technology.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Metabolism comprises the processes that the body needs to function.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Basal metabolic rate is the amount of energy per unit of time that a person needs to keep the body functioning at rest.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Some of those processes are breathing, blood circulation, controlling body temperature, cell growth, brain and nerve function, and contraction of muscles.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Basal metabolic rate affects the rate that a person burns calories and ultimately whether that individual maintains, gains, or loses weight.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The basal metabolic rate accounts for about 70% of the daily calorie expenditure by individuals.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] In humans, BMR typically declines by 1–2% per decade after age 20, mostly due to loss of fat-free mass, although the variability between individuals is high.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The body's generation of heat is known as thermogenesis and it can be measured to determine the amount of energy expended.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] BMR generally decreases with age, and with the decrease in lean body mass (as may happen with aging).
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Increasing muscle mass has the effect of increasing BMR.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Aerobic (resistance) fitness level, a product of cardiovascular exercise, while previously thought to have effect on BMR, has been shown in the 1990s not to correlate with BMR when adjusted for fat-free body mass.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] But anaerobic exercise does increase resting energy consumption (see "aerobic vs. anaerobic exercise").
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Illness, previously consumed food and beverages, environmental temperature, and stress levels can affect one's overall energy expenditure as well as one's BMR.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] BMR is measured under very restrictive circumstances when a person is awake.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] An accurate BMR measurement requires that the person's sympathetic nervous system not be stimulated, a condition which requires complete rest.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] A more common measurement, which uses less strict criteria, is resting metabolic rate (RMR).
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] BMR may be measured by gas analysis through either direct or indirect calorimetry, though a rough estimation can be acquired through an equation using age, sex, height, and weight.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] BMR is a flexible trait (it can be reversibly adjusted within individuals), with, for example, lower temperatures generally resulting in higher basal metabolic rates for both birds and rodents.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] There are two models to explain how BMR changes in response to temperature: the variable maximum model (VMM) and variable fraction model (VFM).
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The VMM states that the summit metabolism (or the maximum metabolic rate in response to the cold) increases during the winter, and that the sustained metabolism (or the metabolic rate that can be indefinitely sustained) remains a constant fraction of the former.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The VFM says that the summit metabolism does not change, but that the sustained metabolism is a larger fraction of it.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The VMM is supported in mammals, and, when using whole-body rates, passerine birds.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The VFM is supported in studies of passerine birds using mass-specific metabolic rates (or metabolic rates per unit of mass).
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] This latter measurement has been criticized by Eric Liknes, Sarah Scott, and David Swanson, who say that mass-specific metabolic rates are inconsistent seasonally.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] In addition to adjusting to temperature, BMR also may adjust before annual migration cycles.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] *islandica*) increases its BMR by about 40% before migrating northward.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] This is because of the energetic demand of long-distance flights.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The increase is likely primarily due to increased mass in organs related to flight.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The end destination of migrants affects their BMR: yellow-rumped warblers migrating northward were found to have a 31% higher BMR than those migrating southward.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] In humans, BMR is directly proportional to a person's lean body mass.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] In other words, the more lean body mass a person has, the higher their BMR; but BMR is also affected by acute illnesses and increases with conditions like burns, fractures, infections, fevers, etc.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] In menstruating females, BMR varies to some extent with the phases of their menstrual cycle.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Due to the increase in progesterone, BMR rises at the start of the luteal phase and stays at its highest until this phase ends.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] There are different findings in research how much of an increase usually occurs.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Small sample, early studies, found various figures, such as; a 6% higher postovulatory sleep metabolism, a 7% to 15% higher 24 hour expenditure following ovulation, and an increase and a luteal phase BMR increase by up to 12%.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] A study by the American Society of Clinical Nutrition found that an experimental group of female volunteers had an 11.5% average increase in 24 hour energy expenditure in the two weeks following ovulation, with a range of 8% to 16%.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] This group was measured via simultaneously direct and indirect calorimetry and had standardized daily meals and sedentary schedule in order to prevent the increase from being manipulated by change in food intake or activity level.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] A 2011 study conducted by the Mandya Institute of Medical Sciences found that during a woman's follicular phase and menstrual cycle is no significant difference in BMR, however the calories burned per hour is significantly higher, up to 18%, during the luteal phase.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Increased state anxiety (stress level) also temporarily increased BMR.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The primary organ responsible for regulating metabolism is the hypothalamus.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The hypothalamus is located on the diencephalon and forms the floor and part of the lateral walls of the third ventricle of the cerebrum.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] All of these functions taken together form a survival mechanism that causes us to sustain the body processes that BMR measures.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The basic metabolic rate varies between individuals.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] One 2005 study of 150 adults representative of the population in Scotland reported basal metabolic rates from as low as 1,027 kilocalories (4,300 kJ) per day to as high as 2,499 kilocalories (10,460 kJ), with a mean BMR of 1,500 kilocalories (6,300 kJ) per day.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Benedict showed that approximate values for BMR could be derived using body surface area (computed from height and weight), age, and sex, along with the oxygen and carbon dioxide measures taken from calorimetry.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Studies also showed that by eliminating the sex differences that occur with the accumulation of adipose tissue by expressing metabolic rate per unit of "fat-free" or lean body mass, the values between sexes for basal metabolism are essentially the same.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The aforementioned 2005 study in particular found that 62% of the variation in BMR among participants was explained by differences in fat free mass (FFM).
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Other factors explaining the variation included fat mass (7%), age (2%), and experimental error including within-subject difference (2%).
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The rest of the variation (27%) was unexplained.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] This remaining difference was not explained by sex, leptin levels, triiodothyronine levels, or by differing tissue size of highly energetic organs such as the brain.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] In a 2012 study of 8780 white obese subjects, it was found that body weight and fat-free mass had similar predictive power when used to estimate BMR, their respective combination with gender and age being able to explain 59% or 60% of the variation.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Gender plays a role in determining BMR in children and adolescents, but not in adults.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] In addition, the age-related reduction in BMR is mostly explained by the decrease in FFM.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The BMR of the average person has also changed over time.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] A cross-sectional study of more than 1400 subjects in Europe and the US showed that once adjusted for differences in body composition (lean and fat mass) and age, BMR has fallen over the past 35 years.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The decline was also observed in a meta-analysis of more than 150 studies dating back to the early 1920s, translating into a decline in total energy expenditure of about 6%.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Several equations to predict the number of calories required by humans have been published from the early 20th–21st centuries.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Historically, accurate measurements of body composition were difficult to obtain.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] As technologies to measure lean body mass directly (e.g.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry) did not exist when early researchers developed these equations, they relied on total body weight, height, age, and sex as proxies for metabolic activity.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The difference in BMR for men and women is mainly due to differences in body mass.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] For example, a 55-year-old woman weighing 130 pounds (59 kg) and 66 inches (168 cm) tall would have a BMR of 1,272 kilocalories (5,320 kJ) per day.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] In 1984, the original Harris–Benedict equations were revised using new data.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] where *s* is +5 for males and −161 for females.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] According to this formula, the woman in the example above has a BMR of 1,204 kilocalories (5,040 kJ) per day.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] During the last 100 years, lifestyles have changed, and Frankenfield *et al.* showed it to be about 5% more accurate.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The following formulas are based on a population of obese white people participating an Italian study.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] where *s* is 0 for females and 1 for males.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] These formulas take into account lean body mass, which makes them potentially more accurate for individuals with body compositions that differ significantly from the average (such as athletes and obese people).
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The Katch–McArdle formula is used to predict resting daily energy expenditure (RDEE).
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The Cunningham formula is commonly cited to predict RMR instead of BMR; however, the formulas provided by Katch–McArdle and Cunningham are the same.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] According to this formula, if the woman in the example has a body fat percentage of 30%, her resting daily energy expenditure (the authors use the term of basal and resting metabolism interchangeably) would be 1262 kcal per day.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Comparing the adult lean-mass formula to the adult body-mass formula, one finds that the weight of gender is markedly reduced.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] (In fact, the confidence interval of the slope includes 0, showing that gender has no statistically significant effect.) The slope for age is also markedly smaller, supporting the idea that age-related decline in BMR is mostly explained by loss of lean mass.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] About 70% of a human's total energy expenditure is due to the basal life processes taking place in the organs of the body (see table).
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] About 20% of one's energy expenditure comes from physical activity and another 10% from thermogenesis, or digestion of food (*postprandial thermogenesis*).
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] All of these processes require an intake of oxygen along with coenzymes to provide energy for survival (usually from macronutrients like carbohydrates, fats, and proteins) and expel carbon dioxide, due to processing by the Krebs cycle.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] For the BMR, most of the energy is consumed in maintaining fluid levels in tissues through osmoregulation, and only about one-tenth is consumed for mechanical work, such as digestion, heartbeat, and breathing.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Exergonic reactions are energy-releasing reactions and are generally catabolic.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Endergonic reactions require energy and include anabolic reactions and the contraction of muscle.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Metabolism is the total of all catabolic, exergonic, anabolic, and endergonic reactions.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Adenosine triphosphate (ATP) is the intermediate molecule that drives the exergonic transfer of energy to switch to endergonic anabolic reactions used in muscle contraction.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] This is what causes muscles to work which can require a breakdown, and also to build in the rest period, which occurs during the strengthening phase associated with muscular contraction.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] ATP is composed of adenine, a nitrogen containing base, ribose, a five carbon sugar (collectively called adenosine), and three phosphate groups.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] ATP is a high energy molecule because it stores large amounts of energy in the chemical bonds of the two terminal phosphate groups.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The breaking of these chemical bonds in the Krebs Cycle provides the energy needed for muscular contraction.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Because the ratio of hydrogen to oxygen atoms in all carbohydrates is always the same as that in water—that is, 2 to 1—all of the oxygen consumed by the cells is used to oxidize the carbon in the carbohydrate molecule to form carbon dioxide.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Consequently, during the complete oxidation of a glucose molecule, six molecules of carbon dioxide and six molecules of water are produced and six molecules of oxygen are consumed.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The chemical composition for fats differs from that of carbohydrates in that fats contain considerably fewer oxygen atoms in proportion to atoms of carbon and hydrogen.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] When listed on nutritional information tables, fats are generally divided into six categories: total fats, saturated fatty acid, polyunsaturated fatty acid, monounsaturated fatty acid, dietary cholesterol, and trans fatty acid.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] From a basal metabolic or resting metabolic perspective, more energy is needed to burn a saturated fatty acid than an unsaturated fatty acid.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The fatty acid molecule is broken down and categorized based on the number of carbon atoms in its molecular structure.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The chemical equation for metabolism of the twelve to sixteen carbon atoms in a saturated fatty acid molecule shows the difference between metabolism of carbohydrates and fatty acids.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Palmitic acid is a commonly studied example of the saturated fatty acid molecule.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Proteins are composed of carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, and nitrogen arranged in a variety of ways to form a large combination of amino acids.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Unlike fat the body has no storage deposits of protein.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] All of it is contained in the body as important parts of tissues, blood hormones, and enzymes.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The structural components of the body that contain these amino acids are continually undergoing a process of breakdown and replacement.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Protein catabolism (breakdown) has been estimated to supply 10% to 15% of the total energy requirement during a two-hour aerobic training session.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] This process could severely degrade the protein structures needed to maintain survival such as contractile properties of proteins in the heart, cellular mitochondria, myoglobin storage, and metabolic enzymes within muscles.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The oxidative system (aerobic) is the primary source of ATP supplied to the body at rest and during low intensity activities and uses primarily carbohydrates and fats as substrates.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Protein is not normally metabolized significantly, except during long term starvation and long bouts of exercise (greater than 90 minutes.) At rest approximately 70% of the ATP produced is derived from fats and 30% from carbohydrates.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Following the onset of activity, as the intensity of the exercise increases, there is a shift in substrate preference from fats to carbohydrates.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] During high intensity aerobic exercise, almost 100% of the energy is derived from carbohydrates, if an adequate supply is available.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Studies published in 1992 and 1997 indicate that the level of aerobic fitness of an individual does not have any correlation with the level of resting metabolism.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Both studies find that aerobic fitness levels do not improve the predictive power of fat free mass for resting metabolic rate.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] However, recent research from the Journal of Applied Physiology, published in 2012, compared resistance training and aerobic training on body mass and fat mass in overweight adults (STRRIDE AT/RT).
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] When time commitment is evaluated against health benefit, aerobic training is the optimal mode of exercise for reducing fat mass and body mass as a primary consideration, and resistance training is good as a secondary factor when aging and lean mass are a concern.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Resistance training causes injuries at a much higher rate than aerobic training.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Compared to resistance training, it was found that aerobic training resulted in a significantly more pronounced reduction of body weight by enhancing the cardiovascular system which is what is the principal factor in metabolic utilization of fat substrates.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Resistance training if time is available is also helpful in post-exercise metabolism, but it is an adjunctive factor because the body needs to heal sufficiently between resistance training episodes, whereas the body can accept aerobic training every day.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] RMR and BMR are measurements of daily consumption of calories.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The majority of studies that are published on this topic look at aerobic exercise because of its efficacy for health and weight management.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Anaerobic exercise, such as weight lifting, builds additional muscle mass.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Muscle contributes to the fat-free mass of an individual and therefore effective results from anaerobic exercise will increase BMR.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] However, the actual effect on BMR is controversial and difficult to enumerate.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Various studies suggest that the resting metabolic rate of trained muscle is around 55 kJ/kg per day; it then follows that even a substantial increase in muscle mass — say 5 kg — would make only a minor impact on BMR.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] In 1926, Raymond Pearl proposed that longevity varies inversely with basal metabolic rate (the "rate of living hypothesis").
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Additionally, the life span of houseflies can be extended by preventing physical activity.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] This theory has been bolstered by several new studies linking lower basal metabolic rate to increased life expectancy, across the animal kingdom—including humans.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Calorie restriction and reduced thyroid hormone levels, both of which decrease the metabolic rate, have been associated with higher longevity in animals.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] However, the ratio of total daily energy expenditure to resting metabolic rate can vary between 1.6 and 8.0 between species of mammals.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Animals also vary in the degree of coupling between oxidative phosphorylation and ATP production, the amount of saturated fat in mitochondrial membranes, the amount of DNA repair, and many other factors that affect maximum life span.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] One problem with understanding the associations of lifespan and metabolism is that changes in metabolism are often confounded by other factors that may affect lifespan.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] For example, under calorie restriction whole body metabolic rate goes down with increasing levels of restriction, but body temperature also follows the same pattern.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] By manipulating the ambient temperature and exposure to wind it was shown in mice and hamsters that body temperature is a more important modulator of lifespan than metabolic rate.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] A person's metabolism varies with their physical condition and activity.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Weight training can have a longer impact on metabolism than aerobic training, but there are no known mathematical formulas that can exactly predict the length and duration of a raised metabolism from trophic changes with anabolic neuromuscular training.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] A decrease in food intake will typically lower the metabolic rate as the body tries to conserve energy.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Researcher Gary Foster estimates that a very low calorie diet of fewer than 800 calories a day would reduce the metabolic rate by more than 10 percent.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The metabolic rate can be affected by some drugs: antithyroid agents (drugs used to treat hyper­thyroid­ism) such as propylthiouracil and methimazole bring the metabolic rate down to normal, restoring euthyroidism.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] Some research has focused on developing antiobesity drugs to raise the metabolic rate, such as drugs to stimulate thermogenesis in skeletal muscle.
[src:energy-consumption/basal-metabolic-rate] The metabolic rate may be elevated in stress, illness, and diabetes.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] In physics and chemistry, **binding energy** is the smallest amount of energy required to remove a particle from a system of particles or to disassemble a system of particles into individual parts.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] In the former meaning the term is predominantly used in condensed matter physics, atomic physics, and chemistry, whereas in nuclear physics the term *separation energy* is used.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] A bound system is typically at a lower energy level than its unbound constituents.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] According to relativity theory, a Δ*E* decrease in the total energy of a system is accompanied by a decrease Δ*m* in the total mass, where Δ*mc*2 = Δ*E*.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] There are several types of binding energy, each operating over a different distance and energy scale.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] The smaller the size of a bound system, the higher its associated binding energy.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] A bound system is typically at a lower energy level than its unbound constituents because its mass must be less than the total mass of its unbound constituents.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] For systems with low binding energies, this "lost" mass after binding may be fractionally small, whereas for systems with high binding energies, the missing mass may be an easily measurable fraction.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] This missing mass may be lost during the process of binding as energy in the form of heat or light, with the removed energy corresponding to the removed mass through Einstein's equation *E* = *mc*2.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] In the process of binding, the constituents of the system might enter higher energy states of the nucleus/atom/molecule while retaining their mass, and because of this, it is necessary that they are removed from the system before its mass can decrease.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] Once the system cools to normal temperatures and returns to ground states regarding energy levels, it will contain less mass than when it first combined and was at high energy.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] This loss of heat represents the "mass deficit", and the heat itself retains the mass that was lost (from the point of view of the initial system).
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] This mass will appear in any other system that absorbs the heat and gains thermal energy.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] For example, if two objects are attracting each other in space through their gravitational field, the attraction force accelerates the objects, increasing their velocity, which converts their potential energy (gravity) into kinetic energy.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] When the particles either pass through each other without interaction or elastically repel during the collision, the gained kinetic energy (related to speed) begins to revert into potential energy, driving the collided particles apart.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] The decelerating particles will return to the initial distance and beyond into infinity, or stop and repeat the collision (oscillation takes place).
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] This shows that the system, which loses no energy, does not combine (bind) into a solid object, parts of which oscillate at short distances.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] Therefore, to bind the particles, the kinetic energy gained due to the attraction must be dissipated by resistive force.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] Complex objects in collision ordinarily undergo inelastic collision, transforming some kinetic energy into internal energy (heat content, which is atomic movement), which is further radiated in the form of photons – the light and heat.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] Once the energy to escape the gravity is dissipated in the collision, the parts will oscillate at a closer, possibly atomic, distance, thus looking like one solid object.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] This lost energy, necessary to overcome the potential barrier to separate the objects, is the binding energy.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] If this binding energy were retained in the system as heat, its mass would not decrease, whereas binding energy lost from the system as heat radiation would itself have mass.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] It directly represents the "mass deficit" of the cold, bound system.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] Closely analogous considerations apply in chemical and nuclear reactions.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] Exothermic chemical reactions in closed systems do not change mass, but do become less massive once the heat of reaction is removed, though this mass change is too small to measure with standard equipment.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] In nuclear reactions, the fraction of mass that may be removed as light or heat, i.e. binding energy, is often a much larger fraction of the system mass.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] It may thus be measured directly as a mass difference between rest masses of reactants and (cooled) products.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] This is because nuclear forces are comparatively stronger than the Coulombic forces associated with the interactions between electrons and protons that generate heat in chemistry.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] Mass change (decrease) in bound systems, particularly atomic nuclei, has also been termed *mass defect*, *mass deficit*, or mass *packing fraction*.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] The difference between the unbound system calculated mass and experimentally measured mass of nucleus (mass change) is denoted as Δ*m*.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] After a nuclear reaction occurs that results in an excited nucleus, the energy that must be radiated or otherwise removed as binding energy in order to decay to the unexcited state may be in one of several forms.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] This may be electromagnetic waves, such as gamma radiation; the kinetic energy of an ejected particle, such as an electron, in internal conversion decay; or partly as the rest mass of one or more emitted particles, such as the particles of beta decay.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] No mass deficit can appear, in theory, until this radiation or this energy has been emitted and is no longer part of the system.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] When nucleons bind together to form a nucleus, they must lose a small amount of mass, i.e. there is a change in mass to stay bound.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] This mass change must be released as various types of photon or other particle energy as above, according to the relation *E* = *mc*2.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] Thus, after the binding energy has been removed, **binding energy = mass change × *c*2**.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] This energy is a measure of the forces that hold the nucleons together.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] It represents energy that must be resupplied from the environment for the nucleus to be broken up into individual nucleons.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] For example, an atom of deuterium has a mass defect of 0.0023884 Da, and its binding energy is nearly equal to 2.23 MeV.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] This means that energy of 2.23 MeV is required to disintegrate an atom of deuterium.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] The energy given off during either nuclear fusion or nuclear fission is the difference of the binding energies of the "fuel", i.e. the initial nuclide(s), from that of the fission or fusion products.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] In practice, this energy may also be calculated from the substantial mass differences between the fuel and products, which uses previous measurements of the atomic masses of known nuclides, which always have the same mass for each species.
[src:energy-consumption/binding-energy] This mass difference appears once evolved heat and radiation have been removed, which is required for measuring the (rest) masses of the (non-excited) nuclides involved in such calculations.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Bioenergy can help with climate change mitigation but in some cases the required biomass production can increase greenhouse gas emissions or lead to local biodiversity loss.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] The environmental impacts of biomass production can be problematic, depending on how the biomass is produced and harvested.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] But it still produces CO2; so long as the energy is derived from breaking chemical bonds.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] The IEA's Net Zero by 2050 scenario calls for traditional bioenergy to be phased out by 2030, with modern bioenergy's share increasing from 6.6% in 2020 to 13.1% in 2030 and 18.7% in 2050.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Bioenergy has a significant climate change mitigation potential if implemented correctly.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Most of the recommended pathways to limit global warming include substantial contributions from bioenergy in 2050 (average at 200 EJ).
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] The IPCC Sixth Assessment Report defines *bioenergy* as "energy derived from any form of biomass or its metabolic by-products".
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] It goes on to define *biomass* in this context as "organic material excluding the material that is fossilised or embedded in geological formations".
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] This means that coal or other fossil fuels is not a form of biomass in this context.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] The term *traditional biomass* for bioenergy means "the combustion of wood, charcoal, agricultural residues and/or animal dung for cooking or heating in open fires or in inefficient stoves as is common in low-income countries".
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Since biomass can also be used as a fuel directly (e.g. wood logs), the terms *biomass* and *biofuel* have sometimes been used interchangeably.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] However, the term *biomass* usually denotes the biological raw material the fuel is made of.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] The terms biofuel or biogas are generally reserved for liquid or gaseous fuels respectively.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Wood and wood residues is the largest biomass energy source today.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Wood can be used as a fuel directly or processed into pellet fuel or other forms of fuels.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Other plants can also be used as fuel, for instance maize, switchgrass, miscanthus and bamboo.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] The main waste feedstocks are wood waste, agricultural waste, municipal solid waste, and manufacturing waste.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Many **chemical conversions** are based on established coal-based processes, such as the Fischer-Tropsch synthesis.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Like coal, biomass can be converted into multiple commodity chemicals.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Biomass heating systems generate heat from biomass.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] The systems may use direct combustion, gasification, combined heat and power (CHP), anaerobic digestion or aerobic digestion to produce heat.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Biomass heating may be fully automated or semi-automated they may be pellet-fired, or they may be combined heat and power systems .
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] First-generation (or "conventional") biofuels are made from *food* sources grown on arable lands, such as sugarcane and maize.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Sugars present in this biomass are fermented to produce bioethanol, an alcohol fuel which serves as an additive to gasoline, or in a fuel cell to produce electricity.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Bioethanol is made by fermentation, mostly from carbohydrates produced in sugar or starch crops such as corn, sugarcane, or sweet sorghum.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Bioethanol is widely used in the United States and in Brazil.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Biodiesel is produced from the oils in for instance rapeseed or sugar beets and is the most common biofuel in Europe.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Second-generation biofuels (also called "advanced biofuels") utilize *non-food*-based biomass sources such as perennial energy crops and agricultural residues/waste.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] The feedstock used to make the fuels either grow on arable land but are byproducts of the main crop, or they are grown on marginal land.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Waste from industry, agriculture, forestry and households can also be used for second-generation biofuels, using e.g. anaerobic digestion to produce biogas, gasification to produce syngas or by direct combustion.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Cellulosic biomass, derived from non-food sources, such as trees and grasses, is being developed as a feedstock for ethanol production, and biodiesel can be produced from left-over food products like vegetable oils and animal fats.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] The surface power production densities of a crop will determine how much land is required for production.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] The average lifecycle surface power densities for biomass, wind, hydro and solar power production are 0.30 W/m2, 1 W/m2, 3 W/m2 and 5 W/m2, respectively (power in the form of heat for biomass, and electricity for wind, hydro and solar).
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Lifecycle surface power density includes land used by all supporting infrastructure, manufacturing, mining/harvesting and decommissioning.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Another estimate puts the values at 0.08 W/m2 for biomass, 0.14 W/m2 for hydro, 1.84 W/m2 for wind, and 6.63 W/m2 for solar (median values, with none of the renewable sources exceeding 10 W/m2).
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Carbon capture and storage technology can be used to capture emissions from bioenergy power plants.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] This process is known as bioenergy with carbon capture and storage (BECCS) and can result in net carbon dioxide removal from the atmosphere.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] However, BECCS can also result in net positive emissions depending on how the biomass material is grown, harvested, and transported.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Deployment of BECCS at scales described in some climate change mitigation pathways would require converting large amounts of cropland.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Bioenergy with carbon capture and storage (BECCS) is the process of extracting bioenergy from biomass and capturing and storing the carbon dioxide (CO2) that is produced.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Greenhouse gas emissions from bioenergy can be low because when vegetation is harvested for bioenergy, new vegetation can grow that will absorb CO2 from the air through photosynthesis.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] After the biomass is harvested, energy ("bioenergy") is extracted in useful forms (electricity, heat, biofuels, etc.) as the biomass is utilized through combustion, fermentation, pyrolysis or other conversion methods.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] In BECCS, some of the CO2 is captured before it enters the atmosphere, and stored underground using carbon capture and storage technology.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Under some conditions, BECCS can remove carbon dioxide from the atmosphere.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] The potential range of negative emissions from BECCS was estimated to be zero to 22 giga tonnes per year.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] As of 2024, there are large-scale 3 BECCS projects operating in the world.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Wide deployment of BECCS is constrained by cost and availability of biomass.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Since biomass production is land-intensive, deployment of BECCS can pose major risks to food production, human rights, and biodiversity.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] The climate impact of bioenergy varies considerably depending on where biomass feedstocks come from and how they are grown.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] For example, burning wood for energy releases carbon dioxide; those emissions can be significantly offset if the trees that were harvested are replaced by new trees in a well-managed forest, as the new trees will absorb carbon dioxide from the air as they grow.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] However, the establishment and cultivation of bioenergy crops can displace natural ecosystems, degrade soils, and consume water resources and synthetic fertilisers.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Approximately one-third of all wood used for traditional heating and cooking in tropical areas is harvested unsustainably.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Bioenergy feedstocks typically require significant amounts of energy to harvest, dry, and transport; the energy usage for these processes may emit greenhouse gases.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] In some cases, the impacts of land-use change, cultivation, and processing can result in higher overall carbon emissions for bioenergy compared to using fossil fuels.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Use of farmland for growing biomass can result in less land being available for growing food.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] In the United States, around 10% of motor gasoline has been replaced by corn-based ethanol, which requires a significant proportion of the harvest.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] In Malaysia and Indonesia, clearing forests to produce palm oil for biodiesel has led to serious social and environmental effects, as these forests are critical carbon sinks and habitats for diverse species.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Since photosynthesis captures only a small fraction of the energy in sunlight, producing a given amount of bioenergy requires a large amount of land compared to other renewable energy sources.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Bioenergy can either mitigate (i.e. reduce) or increase greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Local environmental impacts can be problematic.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] For example, forests are sometimes cleared for the production of sugarcane-derived bioethanol, like in the case of a large-scale project in Indonesia in 2025.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Biomass production can create significant social and environmental pressure in the locations where the biomass is produced.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] The impact is primarily related to the low surface power density of biomass.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] The low surface power density has the effect that much larger land areas are needed in order to produce the same amount of energy, compared to for instance fossil fuels.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Long-distance transport of biomass have been criticised as wasteful and unsustainable, and there have been protests against forest biomass export in Sweden and Canada.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] In 2020 bioenergy produced 58 EJ (exajoules) of energy, compared to 172 EJ from crude oil, 157 EJ from coal, 138 EJ from natural gas, 29 EJ from nuclear, 16 EJ from hydro and 15 EJ from wind, solar and geothermal combined.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Most of the global bioenergy is produced from forest resources.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Generally, bioenergy expansion fell by 50% in 2020.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] China and Europe are the only two regions that reported significant expansion in 2020, adding 2 GW and 1.2 GW of bioenergy capacity, respectively.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Almost all available sawmill residue is already being utilized for pellet production, so there is no room for expansion.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] For the bioenergy sector to significantly expand in the future, more of the harvested pulpwood must go to pellet mills.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] However, the harvest of pulpwood (tree thinnings) removes the possibility for these trees to grow old and therefore maximize their carbon holding capacity.
[src:energy-consumption/bioenergy] Compared to pulpwood, sawmill residues have lower net emissions: "Some types of biomass feedstock can be carbon-neutral, at least over a period of a few years, including in particular sawmill residues.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] The composition of a specific source of biomass depends on whether it is derived from plants, animals, microorganisms, or some mixture of all biological matter.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] Biomass may also contain material from non-biological origin, due to contamination from anthropogenic activities.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] The table below summarizes the main types of biomasses and their typical sources.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] The composition of biomass on a chemical level is determined by whether it is plant or animal matter.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] Biomass is a form of renewable energy useful as fuel and as a source of some chemical products.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] Relative to coal and petroleum however, the energy content of biomass is low.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] Compared to traditional fossil fuels, biomass has a high oxygen content.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] Its carbon is partially combusted, so to speak.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] One such notable example is the production of bio-ethanol.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] There is a general classification of biomass that is produced or sourced for conversion processes.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] Biofuels such as bioethanol and biodiesel, and bioplastics, are typically derived from primary or “first-generation” source energy-dense plants and oils such as rapeseed, sugarcane, or corn.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] Their high content of sugars and oils makes them ideal as feedstocks, however, there are drawbacks to their use.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] As well as inflating the price of the chosen crop due to increased demand, arable land that would otherwise be used to grow food for human and animal consumption is rendered unavailable.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] Secondary or “second-generation” source biomass encompasses a much wider variety of plant and animal matter.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] It may be derived from a relatively pure source, such as wood chippings or grass, or it may be a less well defined solid waste stream.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] This type of biomass is far more challenging to work with, as it contains a more varied mixture of compounds that cannot be easily converted into useful products.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] Despite this, there continues to be intensive research and industry interest in second-generation biomass conversion processes due to its potential to re-use potentially valuable products and derivative products that would otherwise be wasted by incineration.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] In ecological studies, biomass refers to the total amount of biological organisms that are present in a given environment or ecosystem.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] It may encompass the entirety of biological matter, or a subset of species or individuals.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] It is typically expressed as the total weight of carbon that is contained within the chosen group of organisms.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] A 2017 estimate of the total amount of biomass within the biosphere is approximately 550 gigatons of carbon, with a significant majority of this being terrestrial plants (approx.
[src:energy-consumption/biomass] To calculate that, remote sensing techniques such as the Normalized difference vegetation index (NDVI), is commonly used to estimate biomass over large scales.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] A **capacitor** is a device that stores electrical energy by accumulating electric charges on two closely spaced surfaces that are insulated from each other.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] It is a passive electronic component with two terminals.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] A capacitor was originally known as a **condenser**, a term still encountered in a few compound names, such as the *condenser microphone*.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Colloquially, a capacitor may be called a ***cap***.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The utility of a capacitor depends on its capacitance.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] While some capacitance exists between any two electrical conductors in proximity in a circuit, a capacitor is a component designed specifically to add capacitance to some part of the circuit.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The physical form and construction of practical capacitors vary widely and many types of capacitor are in common use.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Most capacitors contain at least two electrical conductors, often in the form of metallic plates or surfaces separated by a dielectric medium.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] A conductor may be a foil, thin film, sintered bead of metal, or an electrolyte.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The nonconducting dielectric acts to increase the capacitor's charge capacity.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Materials commonly used as dielectrics include glass, ceramic, plastic film, paper, mica, air, and oxide layers.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] No current actually flows through a perfect dielectric.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] However, there is a flow of charge through the source circuit.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] If the condition is maintained sufficiently long, the current through the source circuit ceases.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] If a time-varying voltage is applied across the leads of the capacitor, the source experiences an ongoing current due to the charging and discharging cycles of the capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are widely used as parts of electrical circuits in many common electrical devices.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Unlike a resistor, an ideal capacitor does not dissipate energy, although real-life capacitors do dissipate a small amount .
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The earliest forms of capacitors were created in the 1740s, when European experimenters discovered that electric charge could be stored in water-filled glass jars that came to be known as Leyden jars.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Today, capacitors are widely used in electronic circuits for blocking direct current while allowing alternating current to pass.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In analog filter networks, they smooth the output of power supplies.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In resonant circuits they tune radios to particular frequencies.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In electric power transmission systems, they stabilize voltage and power flow.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The property of energy storage in capacitors was exploited as dynamic memory in early digital computers, and still is in modern DRAM.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The most common example of natural capacitance are the static charges accumulated between clouds in the sky and the surface of the Earth, where the air between them serves as the dielectric.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] This results in bolts of lightning when the breakdown voltage of the air is exceeded.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In October 1745, Ewald Georg von Kleist of Pomerania, Germany, found that charge could be stored by connecting a high-voltage electrostatic generator by a wire to a volume of water in a hand-held glass jar.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Von Kleist's hand and the water acted as conductors and the jar as a dielectric (although details of the mechanism were incorrectly identified at the time).
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Von Kleist found that touching the wire resulted in a powerful spark, much more painful than that obtained from an electrostatic machine.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The following year, the Dutch physicist Pieter van Musschenbroek invented a similar capacitor, which was named the Leyden jar, after the University of Leiden where he worked.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Daniel Gralath was the first to combine several jars in parallel to increase the charge storage capacity.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Benjamin Franklin investigated the Leyden jar and came to the conclusion that the charge was stored on the glass, not in the water as others had assumed.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] He also adopted the term "battery", (denoting the increase of power with a row of similar units as in a battery of cannon), subsequently applied to clusters of electrochemical cells.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In 1747, Leyden jars were made by coating the inside and outside of jars with metal foil, leaving a space at the mouth to prevent arcing between the foils.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The earliest unit of capacitance was the jar, equivalent to about 1.11 nanofarads.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] More compact construction methods began to be used, such as a flexible dielectric sheet (like oiled paper) sandwiched between sheets of metal foil, rolled or folded into a small package.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Early capacitors were known as *condensers*, a term that is still occasionally used today, particularly in high power applications, such as automotive systems.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The term became deprecated because of the ambiguous meaning of steam condenser, with *capacitor* being recommended by the British Engineering Standards Association in 1926, although it took several decades for the term to predominate.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Since the beginning of the study of electricity, non-conductive materials like glass, porcelain, paper and mica have been used as insulators.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Decades later, these materials were also well-suited for use as the dielectric for the first capacitors.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Paper capacitors, made by sandwiching a strip of impregnated paper between strips of metal and rolling the result into a cylinder, were commonly used in the late 19th century; their manufacture started in 1876, and they were used from the early 20th century as decoupling capacitors in telephony.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Porcelain was used in the first ceramic capacitors.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In the early years of Marconi's wireless transmitting apparatus, porcelain capacitors were used for high voltage and high frequency application in the transmitters.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] On the receiver side, smaller mica capacitors were used for resonant circuits.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Mica capacitors were invented in 1909 by William Dubilier.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Prior to World War II, mica was the most common dielectric for capacitors in the United States.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Charles Pollak (born Karol Pollak), the inventor of the first electrolytic capacitors, found out that the oxide layer on an aluminum anode remained stable in a neutral or alkaline electrolyte, even when the power was switched off.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] 672,913 for an "Electric liquid capacitor with aluminum electrodes".
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Solid electrolyte tantalum capacitors were invented by Bell Laboratories in the early 1950s as a miniaturized and more reliable low-voltage support capacitor to complement their newly invented transistor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] With the development of plastic materials by organic chemists during the Second World War, the capacitor industry began to replace paper with thinner polymer films.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] One very early development in film capacitors was described in British Patent 587,953 in 1944.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Electric double-layer capacitors (now supercapacitors) were invented in 1957 when H.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Becker developed a "Low voltage electrolytic capacitor with porous carbon electrodes".
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] He believed that the energy was stored as a charge in the carbon pores used in his capacitor as in the pores of the etched foils of electrolytic capacitors.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The MOS capacitor was later widely adopted as a storage capacitor in memory chips, and as the basic building block of the charge-coupled device (CCD) in image sensor technology.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Robert Dennard invented modern DRAM architecture, combining a single MOS transistor per capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] A capacitor consists of two conductors separated by a non-conductive region.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The non-conductive region can either be a vacuum or an electrical insulator material known as a dielectric.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Examples of dielectric media are glass, air, paper, plastic, ceramic, and even a semiconductor depletion region chemically identical to the conductors.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] From Coulomb's law, a charge on one conductor will exert a force on the charge carriers within the other conductor, attracting opposite polarity charge and repelling like polarity charges, thus an opposite polarity charge will be induced on the surface of the other conductor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The conductors thus hold equal and opposite charges on their facing surfaces, and the dielectric develops an electric field.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] A capacitance of one farad (1 F) means that one coulomb of charge on each conductor causes a voltage of one volt across the device.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Because the conductors (or plates) are close together, the opposite charges on the conductors attract one another due to their electric fields, allowing the capacitor to store more charge for a given voltage than when the conductors are separated, yielding a larger capacitance.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In practical devices, charge build-up sometimes affects the capacitor mechanically, causing its capacitance to vary.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In the hydraulic analogy, voltage is analogous to water pressure and electrical current through a wire is analogous to water flow through a pipe.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] A capacitor is like an elastic diaphragm within the pipe.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Although water cannot pass through the diaphragm, it moves as the diaphragm stretches or un-stretches.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In a circuit, a capacitor can behave differently at different time instants.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The simplest model of a capacitor consists of two thin parallel conductive plates each with an area of A separated by a uniform gap of thickness d filled with a dielectric of permittivity ⁠ $\varepsilon$ ⁠.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] It is assumed the gap d is much smaller than the dimensions of the plates.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] This model applies well to many practical capacitors which are constructed of metal sheets separated by a thin layer of insulating dielectric, since manufacturers try to keep the dielectric very uniform in thickness to avoid thin spots which can cause failure of the capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] This "fringing field" area is approximately the same width as the plate separation, ⁠ d ⁠, and assuming d is small compared to the plate dimensions, it is small enough to be ignored.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] From Gauss's law the magnitude of the electric field between the plates is ⁠ $\textstyle E={\sigma \over \varepsilon }$ ⁠.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Therefore, in a capacitor the highest capacitance is achieved with a high permittivity dielectric material, large plate area, and small separation between the plates.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Since the area A of the plates increases with the square of the linear dimensions and the separation d increases linearly, the capacitance scales with the linear dimension of a capacitor (⁠ $C\varpropto L$ ⁠), or as the cube root of the volume.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] A parallel plate capacitor can only store a finite amount of energy before dielectric breakdown occurs.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The capacitor's dielectric material has a dielectric strength *U*d which sets the capacitor's breakdown voltage at *V* = *V*bd = *U*d*d*.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The maximum energy is a function of dielectric volume, permittivity, and dielectric strength.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Changing the plate area and the separation between the plates while maintaining the same volume causes no change of the maximum amount of energy that the capacitor can store, so long as the distance between plates remains much smaller than both the length and width of the plates.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In addition, these equations assume that the electric field is entirely concentrated in the dielectric between the plates.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In reality there are fringing fields outside the dielectric, for example between the sides of the capacitor plates, which increase the effective capacitance of the capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] This is sometimes called parasitic capacitance.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] For some simple capacitor geometries this additional capacitance term can be calculated analytically.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] It becomes negligibly small when the ratios of plate width to separation and length to separation are large.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] For n number of plates in a capacitor, the total capacitance would be $C=\varepsilon _{o}{\frac {A}{d}}(n-1)$ where ${\textstyle C={\frac {\varepsilon _{o}A}{d}}}$ is the capacitance for a single plate and n is the number of interleaved plates.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] As shown to the figure on the right, the interleaved plates can be seen as parallel plates connected to each other.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Every pair of adjacent plates acts as a separate capacitor; the number of pairs is always one less than the number of plates, hence the $(n-1)$ multiplier.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] To increase the charge and voltage on a capacitor, work must be done by an external power source to move charge from the negative to the positive plate against the opposing force of the electric field.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] If the voltage on the capacitor is ⁠ V ⁠, the work $\mathrm {d} W$ required to move a small increment of charge $\mathrm {d} q$ from the negative to the positive plate is ⁠ $\mathrm {d} W=V\mathop {} \!\mathrm {d} q$ ⁠.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The energy is stored in the increased electric field between the plates.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] This potential energy will remain in the capacitor until the charge is removed.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] If charge is allowed to move back from the positive to the negative plate, for example by connecting a circuit with resistance between the plates, the charge moving under the influence of the electric field will do work on the external circuit.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] If the gap between the capacitor plates d is constant, as in the parallel plate model above, the electric field between the plates will be uniform (neglecting fringing fields) and will have a constant value ⁠ $E=V/d$ ⁠.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The current $I(t)$ through any component in an electric circuit is defined as the rate of flow of a charge $Q(t)$ passing through it.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Actual charges – electrons – cannot pass through the dielectric of an *ideal* capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Rather, one electron accumulates on the negative plate for each one that leaves the positive plate, resulting in an electron depletion and consequent positive charge on one electrode that is equal and opposite to the accumulated negative charge on the other.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Thus the charge on the electrodes is equal to the integral of the current as well as proportional to the voltage, as discussed above.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] As with any antiderivative, a constant of integration is added to represent the initial voltage ⁠ $V(t_{0})$ ⁠).
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] for C independent of time, voltage and electric charge.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The dual of the capacitor is the inductor, which stores energy in a magnetic field rather than an electric field.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Its current-voltage relation is obtained by exchanging current and voltage in the capacitor equations and replacing C with the inductance L.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] A series circuit containing only a resistor, a capacitor, a switch and a constant DC source of voltage *V*0 is known as a *charging circuit*.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] At *t* = 0, the voltage across the capacitor is zero and the voltage across the resistor is *V*0.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The initial current is then ⁠ $\textstyle I(0)={V_{0} \over R}$ ⁠.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] As the capacitor reaches equilibrium with the source voltage, the voltages across the resistor and the current through the entire circuit decay exponentially.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In the case of a *discharging* capacitor, the capacitor's initial voltage (*V*Ci) replaces *V*0.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Impedance, the vector sum of reactance and resistance, describes the phase difference and the ratio of amplitudes between sinusoidally varying voltage and sinusoidally varying current at a given frequency.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Fourier analysis allows any signal to be constructed from a spectrum of frequencies, whence the circuit's reaction to the various frequencies may be found.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The ⁠ $-j$ ⁠ phase indicates that the AC voltage ⁠ $V=ZI$ ⁠ lags the AC current by 90°: the positive current phase corresponds to increasing voltage as the capacitor charges; zero current corresponds to instantaneous constant voltage.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Impedance decreases with increasing capacitance and increasing frequency.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] This implies that a higher-frequency signal or a larger capacitor results in a lower voltage amplitude per current amplitude – an AC "short circuit" or AC coupling.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Conversely, for very low frequencies, the reactance is high, so that a capacitor is nearly an open circuit in AC analysis – those frequencies have been "filtered out".
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are different from resistors and inductors in that the impedance is *inversely* proportional to the defining characteristic; i.e., capacitance.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] A capacitor connected to an alternating voltage source has a displacement current to flowing through it.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] At ⁠ $\sin(\omega t)=-1$ ⁠, the capacitor has a maximum (or peak) current whereby ⁠ $I_{0}=\omega CV_{0}$ ⁠.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In this situation, the current is out of phase with the voltage by ⁠ $\textstyle +{\pi \over 2}$ ⁠ radians or +90 degrees, i.e. the current leads the voltage by 90°.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Capacitors in a parallel configuration each have the same applied voltage.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Charge is apportioned among them by capacitance value.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Connected in series, the schematic diagram reveals that the separation distance, not the plate area, adds up.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The capacitors each store instantaneous charge build-up equal to that of every other capacitor in the series.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The total voltage difference from end to end is apportioned to each capacitor according to the inverse of its capacitance.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are combined in series to achieve a higher working voltage, for example for smoothing a high voltage power supply.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The voltage ratings, which are based on plate separation, add up, if capacitance and leakage currents for each capacitor are identical.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In such an application, on occasion, series strings are connected in parallel, forming a matrix.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The goal is to maximize the energy storage of the network without overloading any capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] For high-energy storage with capacitors in series, some safety considerations must be applied to ensure one capacitor failing and leaking current does not apply too much voltage to the other series capacitors.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Series connection is also sometimes used to adapt polarized electrolytic capacitors for bipolar AC use.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] (Note that this is only correct if all capacitance values are equal).
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In practice, capacitors deviate from the ideal capacitor equation in several aspects.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Some of these, such as leakage current and parasitic effects are linear, or can be analyzed as nearly linear, and can be accounted for by adding virtual components to form an equivalent circuit.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The usual methods of network analysis can then be applied.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In other cases, such as with breakdown voltage, the effect is non-linear and ordinary (normal, e.g., linear) network analysis cannot be used, the effect must be considered separately.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Yet another group of artifacts may exist, including temperature dependence, that may be linear but invalidates the assumption in the analysis that capacitance is a constant.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Finally, combined parasitic effects such as inherent inductance, resistance, or dielectric losses can exhibit non-uniform behavior at varying frequencies of operation.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Above a particular electric field strength, known as the dielectric strength ⁠ $E_{\mathrm {ds} }$ ⁠, the dielectric in a capacitor becomes conductive.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The maximum energy that can be stored safely in a capacitor is limited by the breakdown voltage.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Exceeding this voltage can result in a short circuit between the plates, which can often cause permanent damage to the dielectric, plates, or both.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Due to the scaling of capacitance and breakdown voltage with dielectric thickness, all capacitors made with a particular dielectric have approximately equal maximum energy density, to the extent that the dielectric dominates their volume.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] For air dielectric capacitors the breakdown field strength is of the order 2–5 MV/m (or equivalently in kilovolts per millimeter); for mica the breakdown is 100–300 MV/m; for oil, 15–25 MV/m; it can be much less when other materials are used for the dielectric.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The dielectric is used in very thin layers and so absolute breakdown voltage of capacitors is limited.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Typical ratings for capacitors used for general electronics applications range from a few volts to 1 kilovolt.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] As the voltage increases, the dielectric must be thicker, making high-voltage capacitors larger per capacitance than those rated for lower voltages.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The breakdown voltage is critically affected by factors such as the geometry of the capacitor conductive parts; sharp edges or points increase the electric field strength at that point and can lead to a local breakdown.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Once this starts to happen, the breakdown quickly tracks through the dielectric until it reaches the opposite plate, leaving carbon behind and causing a short (or relatively low resistance) circuit.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The results can be explosive, as the short in the capacitor draws current from the surrounding circuitry and dissipates the energy.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] However, in capacitors with particular dielectrics and thin metal electrodes, shorts are not formed after breakdown.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] It happens because a metal melts or evaporates in a breakdown vicinity, isolating it from the rest of the capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The usual breakdown route is that the field strength becomes large enough to pull electrons in the dielectric from their atoms thus causing conduction.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Other scenarios are possible, such as impurities in the dielectric, and, if the dielectric is of a crystalline nature, imperfections in the crystal structure can result in an avalanche breakdown as seen in semi-conductor devices.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Breakdown voltage is also affected by pressure, humidity and temperature.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] An ideal capacitor only stores and releases electrical energy, without dissipation.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] As frequency increases, the capacitive impedance (a negative reactance) reduces, so the dielectric's conductance becomes less important and the series components become more significant.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Thus, a simplified RLC series model valid for a large frequency range simply treats the capacitor as being in series with an equivalent series inductance ${\text{ESL}}$ and a frequency-dependent *equivalent series resistance* ${\text{ESR}}$ , which varies little with frequency.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Unlike the previous model, this model is not valid at DC and very low frequencies where $G_{\text{dielectric}}$ is relevant.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Inductive reactance increases with frequency.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Because its sign is positive, it counteracts the capacitance.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] At the RLC circuit's natural frequency $\omega _{0}{=}{\tfrac {1}{\sqrt {{\text{ESL}}\cdot {\text{C}}}}}$ , the inductance perfectly cancels the capacitance, so total reactance is zero.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Since the total impedance at $\omega _{0}$ is just the real-value of ${\text{ESR}}$ , average power dissipation reaches its maximum of ⁠VRMS2/ESR⁠, where VRMS is the root mean square (RMS) voltage across the capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] At even higher frequencies, the inductive impedance dominates, so the capacitor undesirably behaves instead like an inductor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] High-frequency engineering involves accounting for the inductance of all connections and components.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The ⁠ Q ⁠ factor is a measure of its efficiency: the higher the ⁠ Q ⁠ factor of the capacitor, the closer it approaches the behavior of an ideal capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Ripple current is the AC component of an applied source (often a switched-mode power supply) whose frequency may be constant or varying.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Ripple current causes heat to be generated within the capacitor due to the dielectric losses caused by the changing field strength together with the current flow across the slightly resistive supply lines or the electrolyte in the capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The equivalent series resistance (ESR) is the amount of internal series resistance one would add to a perfect capacitor to model this.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Some types of capacitors, primarily tantalum and aluminum electrolytic capacitors, as well as some film capacitors have a specified rating value for maximum ripple current.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The capacitance of certain capacitors decreases as the component ages.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In ceramic capacitors, this is caused by degradation of the dielectric.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The type of dielectric, ambient operating and storage temperatures are the most significant aging factors, while the operating voltage usually has a smaller effect, i.e., usual capacitor design is to minimize voltage coefficient.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The aging process may be reversed by heating the component above the Curie point.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Aging is fastest near the beginning of life of the component, and the device stabilizes over time.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors age as the electrolyte evaporates.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In contrast with ceramic capacitors, this occurs towards the end of life of the component.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Temperature dependence of capacitance is usually expressed in parts per million (ppm) per °C.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] It can usually be taken as a broadly linear function but can be noticeably non-linear at the temperature extremes.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The temperature coefficient may be positive or negative, depending mostly on the dielectric material.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Some, designated C0G/NP0, but called **NPO**, have a somewhat negative coefficient at one temperature, positive at another, and zero in between.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Such components may be specified for temperature-critical circuits.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Capacitors, especially ceramic capacitors, and older designs such as paper capacitors, can absorb sound waves resulting in a microphonic effect.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Vibration moves the plates, causing the capacitance to vary, in turn inducing AC current.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Some dielectrics also generate piezoelectricity.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The resulting interference is especially problematic in audio applications, potentially causing feedback or unintended recording.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In the reverse microphonic effect, the varying electric field between the capacitor plates exerts a physical force, moving them as a speaker.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] This can generate audible sound, but drains energy and stresses the dielectric and the electrolyte, if any.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Current reversal occurs when the current changes direction.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Voltage reversal is the change of polarity in a circuit.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Reversal is generally described as the percentage of the maximum rated voltage that reverses polarity.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In DC circuits, this is usually less than 100%, often in the range of 0 to 90%, whereas AC circuits experience 100% reversal.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In DC circuits and pulsed circuits, current and voltage reversal are affected by the damping of the system.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Voltage reversal is encountered in RLC circuits that are underdamped.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The current and voltage reverse direction, forming a harmonic oscillator between the inductance and capacitance.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The current and voltage tends to oscillate and may reverse direction several times, with each peak being lower than the previous, until the system reaches an equilibrium.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In comparison, critically damped or overdamped systems usually do not experience a voltage reversal.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Reversal is also encountered in AC circuits, where the peak current is equal in each direction.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] For maximum life, capacitors usually need to be able to handle the maximum amount of reversal that a system may experience.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] An AC circuit experiences 100% voltage reversal, while underdamped DC circuits experience less than 100%.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Reversal creates excess electric fields in the dielectric, causes excess heating of both the dielectric and the conductors, and can dramatically shorten the life expectancy of the capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Reversal ratings often affect the design considerations for the capacitor, from the choice of dielectric materials and voltage ratings to the types of internal connections used.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Capacitors made with any type of dielectric material show some level of "dielectric absorption" or "soakage".
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] On discharging a capacitor and disconnecting it, after a short time it may develop a voltage due to hysteresis in the dielectric.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] This effect is objectionable in applications such as precision sample and hold circuits or timing circuits.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The level of absorption depends on many factors, from design considerations to charging time, since the absorption is a time-dependent process.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] However, the primary factor is the type of dielectric material.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Capacitors such as tantalum electrolytic or polysulfone film exhibit relatively high absorption, while polystyrene or Teflon allow very small levels of absorption.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In some capacitors where dangerous voltages and energies exist, such as in flashtubes, television sets, microwave ovens and defibrillators, the dielectric absorption can recharge the capacitor to hazardous voltages after it has been shorted or discharged.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Any capacitor containing over 10 joules of energy is generally considered hazardous, while 50 joules or higher is potentially lethal.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] A capacitor may regain anywhere from 0.01 to 20% of its original charge over a period of several minutes, allowing a seemingly safe capacitor to become surprisingly dangerous.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] No material is a perfect insulator, thus all dielectrics allow some small level of current to leak through, which can be measured with a megohmmeter.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Leakage is equivalent to a resistor in parallel with the capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Constant exposure to factors such as heat, mechanical stress, or humidity can cause the dielectric to deteriorate resulting in excessive leakage, a problem often seen in older vacuum tube circuits, particularly where oiled paper and foil capacitors were used.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In many vacuum tube circuits, interstage coupling capacitors are used to conduct a varying signal from the plate of one tube to the grid circuit of the next stage.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] A leaky capacitor can cause the grid circuit voltage to be raised from its normal bias setting, causing excessive current or signal distortion in the downstream tube.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] In power amplifiers this can cause the plates to glow red, or current limiting resistors to overheat, even fail.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Similar considerations apply to component fabricated solid-state (transistor) amplifiers, but, owing to lower heat production and the use of modern polyester dielectric-barriers, this once-common problem has become relatively rare.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Aluminum electrolytic capacitors are *conditioned* when manufactured by applying a voltage sufficient to initiate the proper internal chemical state.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] This state is maintained by regular use of the equipment.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] If a system using electrolytic capacitors is unused for a long period of time it can lose its conditioning.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Sometimes they fail with a short circuit when next operated.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] All capacitors have varying lifespans, depending upon their construction, operational conditions, and environmental conditions.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Solid-state ceramic capacitors generally have very long lives under normal use, which has little dependency on factors such as vibration or ambient temperature, but factors like humidity, mechanical stress, and fatigue play a primary role in their failure.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Some capacitors may experience a gradual loss of capacitance, increased leakage or an increase in equivalent series resistance (ESR), while others may fail suddenly or even catastrophically.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] For example, metal-film capacitors are more prone to damage from stress and humidity, but will self-heal when a breakdown in the dielectric occurs.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The formation of a glow discharge at the point of failure prevents arcing by vaporizing the metallic film in that spot, neutralizing any short circuit with minimal loss in capacitance.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] When enough pinholes accumulate in the film, a total failure occurs in a metal-film capacitor, generally happening suddenly without warning.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors generally have the shortest lifespans.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors are affected very little by vibration or humidity, but factors such as ambient and operational temperatures play a large role in their failure, which gradually occur as an increase in ESR (up to 300%) and as much as a 20% decrease in capacitance.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] The capacitors contain electrolytes which will eventually diffuse through the seals and evaporate.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] An increase in temperature also increases internal pressure, and increases the reaction rate of the chemicals.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] Manufacturers often use this equation to supply an expected lifespan, in hours, for electrolytic capacitors when used at their designed operating temperature, which is affected by both ambient temperature, ESR, and ripple current.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p01] However, these ideal conditions may not exist in every use.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Practical capacitors are available commercially in many different forms.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The type of internal dielectric, the structure of the plates and the device packaging all strongly affect the characteristics of the capacitor, and its applications.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Values available range from very low (picofarad range; while arbitrarily low values are in principle possible, stray (parasitic) capacitance in any circuit is the limiting factor) to about 5 kF supercapacitors.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Above approximately 1 microfarad electrolytic capacitors are usually used because of their small size and low cost compared with other types, unless their relatively poor stability, life and polarised nature make them unsuitable.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Very high capacity supercapacitors use a porous carbon-based electrode material.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors have a dielectric spacer, which increases their capacitance compared to air or a vacuum.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] In order to maximise the charge that a capacitor can hold, the dielectric material needs to have as high a permittivity as possible, while also having as high a breakdown voltage as possible.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The dielectric also needs to have as low a loss with frequency as possible.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] However, low value capacitors are available with a high vacuum between their plates to allow extremely high voltage operation and low losses.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Variable capacitors with their plates open to the atmosphere were commonly used in radio tuning circuits.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Later designs use polymer foil dielectric between the moving and stationary plates, with no significant air space between the plates.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Several solid dielectrics are available, including paper, plastic, glass, mica and ceramic.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Paper was used extensively in older capacitors and offers relatively high voltage performance.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] However, paper absorbs moisture, and has been largely replaced by plastic film capacitors.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Large plastic film capacitors are used extensively in suppression circuits, motor start circuits, and power-factor correction circuits.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Ceramic capacitors are generally small, cheap and useful for high frequency applications, although their capacitance varies strongly with voltage and temperature and they age poorly.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] They can also suffer from the piezoelectric effect.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Ceramic capacitors are broadly categorized as class 1 dielectrics, which have predictable variation of capacitance with temperature or class 2 dielectrics, which can operate at higher voltage.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Modern multilayer ceramics are usually quite small, but some types have inherently wide value tolerances, microphonic issues, and are usually physically brittle.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Glass and mica capacitors are extremely reliable, stable and tolerant to high temperatures and voltages, but are too expensive for most mainstream applications.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors use an aluminum or tantalum plate with an oxide dielectric layer.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The second electrode is a liquid electrolyte, connected to the circuit by another foil plate.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors offer very high capacitance but suffer from poor tolerances, high instability, gradual loss of capacitance especially when subjected to heat, and high leakage current.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Poor quality capacitors may leak electrolyte, which is harmful to printed circuit boards.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The conductivity of the electrolyte drops at low temperatures, which increases equivalent series resistance.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] While widely used for power-supply conditioning, poor high-frequency characteristics make them unsuitable for many applications.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors suffer from self-degradation if unused for a period (around a year), and when full power is applied may short circuit, permanently damaging the capacitor and usually blowing a fuse or causing failure of rectifier diodes.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] For example, in older equipment, this may cause arcing in rectifier tubes.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] They can be restored before use by gradually applying the operating voltage, often performed on antique vacuum tube equipment over a period of thirty minutes by using a variable transformer to supply AC power.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The use of this technique may be less satisfactory for some solid state equipment, which may be damaged by operation below its normal power range, requiring that the power supply first be isolated from the consuming circuits.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Such remedies may not be applicable to modern high-frequency power supplies as these produce full output voltage even with reduced input.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Tantalum capacitors offer better frequency and temperature characteristics than aluminum, but higher dielectric absorption and leakage.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Polymer capacitors (OS-CON, OC-CON, KO, AO) use solid conductive polymer (or polymerized organic semiconductor) as electrolyte and offer longer life and lower ESR at higher cost than standard electrolytic capacitors.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] A feedthrough capacitor is a component that, while not serving as its main use, has capacitance and is used to conduct signals through a conductive sheet.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Several other types of capacitor are available for specialist applications.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Supercapacitors store large amounts of energy.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Supercapacitors made from carbon aerogel, carbon nanotubes, or highly porous electrode materials, offer extremely high capacitance (up to 5 kF as of 2010) and can be used in some applications instead of rechargeable batteries.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Alternating current capacitors are specifically designed to work on line (mains) voltage AC power circuits.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] They are commonly used in electric motor circuits and are often designed to handle large currents, so they tend to be physically large.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] They are usually ruggedly packaged, often in metal cases that can be easily grounded/earthed.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] They also are designed with direct current breakdown voltages of at least five times the maximum AC voltage.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The dielectric constant for a number of very useful dielectrics changes as a function of the applied electrical field, for example ferroelectric materials, so the capacitance for these devices is more complex.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] This field polarizes the dielectric, which polarization, in the case of a ferroelectric, is a nonlinear *S*-shaped function of the electric field, which, in the case of a large area parallel plate device, translates into a capacitance that is a nonlinear function of the voltage.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Corresponding to the voltage-dependent capacitance, to charge the capacitor to voltage V an integral relation is found: $Q=\int _{0}^{V}C(V)\mathop {} \!\mathrm {d} V$ which agrees with *Q* = *CV* only when C does not depend on voltage V.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The nonlinear capacitance of a microscope probe scanned along a ferroelectric surface is used to study the domain structure of ferroelectric materials.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Another example of voltage dependent capacitance occurs in semiconductor devices such as semiconductor diodes, where the voltage dependence stems not from a change in dielectric constant but in a voltage dependence of the spacing between the charges on the two sides of the capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] This effect is intentionally exploited in diode-like devices known as varicaps.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] If a capacitor is driven with a time-varying voltage that changes rapidly enough, at some frequency the polarization of the dielectric cannot follow the voltage.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] As an example of the origin of this mechanism, the internal microscopic dipoles contributing to the dielectric constant cannot move instantly, and so as frequency of an applied alternating voltage increases, the dipole response is limited and the dielectric constant diminishes.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] A changing dielectric constant with frequency is referred to as dielectric dispersion, and is governed by dielectric relaxation processes, such as Debye relaxation.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] indicating the lag in response by the time dependence of *εr*, calculated in principle from an underlying microscopic analysis, for example, of the dipole behavior in the dielectric.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] See, for example, linear response function.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The integral extends over the entire past history up to the present time.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] where *ε*r(*ω*) is now a complex function, with an imaginary part related to absorption of energy from the field by the medium.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The capacitance, being proportional to the dielectric constant, also exhibits this frequency behavior.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] (Measurement "without the dielectric" in principle means measurement in free space, an unattainable goal inasmuch as even the quantum vacuum is predicted to exhibit nonideal behavior, such as dichroism.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Using this measurement method, the dielectric constant may exhibit a resonance at certain frequencies corresponding to characteristic response frequencies (excitation energies) of contributors to the dielectric constant.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] These resonances are the basis for a number of experimental techniques for detecting defects.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The *conductance method* measures absorption as a function of frequency.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Alternatively, the time response of the capacitance can be used directly, as in *deep-level transient spectroscopy*.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Another example of frequency dependent capacitance occurs with MOS capacitors, where the slow generation of minority carriers means that at high frequencies the capacitance measures only the majority carrier response, while at low frequencies both types of carrier respond.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] At optical frequencies, in semiconductors the dielectric constant exhibits structure related to the band structure of the solid.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Sophisticated modulation spectroscopy measurement methods based upon modulating the crystal structure by pressure or by other stresses and observing the related changes in absorption or reflection of light have advanced our knowledge of these materials.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The arrangement of plates and dielectric has many variations in different styles depending on the desired ratings of the capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] For small values of capacitance (microfarads and less), ceramic disks use metallic coatings, with wire leads bonded to the coating.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Larger values can be made by multiple stacks of plates and disks.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Larger value capacitors usually use a metal foil or metal film layer deposited on the surface of a dielectric film to make the plates, and a dielectric film of impregnated paper or plastic – these are rolled up to save space.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] To reduce the series resistance and inductance for long plates, the plates and dielectric are staggered so that connection is made at the common edge of the rolled-up plates, not at the ends of the foil or metalized film strips that comprise the plates.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The assembly is encased to prevent moisture entering the dielectric – early radio equipment used a cardboard tube sealed with wax.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Modern paper or film dielectric capacitors are dipped in a hard thermoplastic.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Large capacitors for high-voltage use may have the roll form compressed to fit into a rectangular metal case, with bolted terminals and bushings for connections.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The dielectric in larger capacitors is often impregnated with a liquid to improve its properties.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may have their connecting leads arranged in many configurations, for example axially or radially.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] "Axial" means that the leads are on a common axis, typically the axis of the capacitor's cylindrical body – the leads extend from opposite ends.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Radial leads are rarely aligned along radii of the body's circle, so the term is conventional.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The leads (until bent) are usually in planes parallel to that of the flat body of the capacitor, and extend in the same direction; they are often parallel as manufactured.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Small, cheap discoidal ceramic capacitors have existed from the 1930s onward, and remain in widespread use.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] After the 1980s, surface mount packages for capacitors have been widely used.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] These packages are extremely small and lack connecting leads, allowing them to be soldered directly onto the surface of printed circuit boards.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Surface mount components avoid undesirable high-frequency effects due to the leads and simplify automated assembly, although manual handling is made difficult due to their small size.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Mechanically controlled variable capacitors allow the plate spacing to be adjusted, for example by rotating or sliding a set of movable plates into alignment with a set of stationary plates.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Low cost variable capacitors squeeze together alternating layers of aluminum and plastic with a screw.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Electrical control of capacitance is achievable with varactors (or varicaps), which are reverse-biased semiconductor diodes whose depletion region width varies with applied voltage.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] They are used in phase-locked loops, amongst other applications.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors have designations printed on their bodies to indicate their electrical characteristics.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors, such as electrolytic types usually display the capacitance as value with explicit unit, for example, *220 μF*.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] For typographical reasons, some manufacturers print *MF* on capacitors to indicate microfarads (μF).
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Smaller capacitors, such as ceramic types, often use a shorthand-notation consisting of three digits and an optional letter, where the digits (*XYZ*) denote the capacitance in picofarad (pF), calculated as *XY* × 10*Z*, and the letter indicating the tolerance.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Common tolerances are ±5%, ±10%, and ±20%, denoted as J, K, and M, respectively.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] A capacitor may also be labeled with its working voltage, temperature, and other relevant characteristics.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Example: A capacitor labeled or designated as *473K 330V* has a capacitance of 47×103 pF = 47 nF (±10%) with a maximum working voltage of 330 V.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The working voltage of a capacitor is nominally the highest voltage that may be applied across it without undue risk of breaking down the dielectric layer.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The code consists of an uppercase letter denoting the two significant digits of the value followed by a digit indicating the multiplier.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The EIA standard also defines a number of lowercase letters to specify a number of values not found in E24.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The RKM code following IEC 60062 and BS 1852 is a notation to state a capacitor's value in a circuit diagram.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] It avoids using a decimal separator and replaces the decimal separator with the SI prefix symbol for the particular value (and the letter F for weight 1).
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The code is also used for part markings.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] In texts prior to the 1960s and on some capacitor packages until more recently, obsolete capacitance units were utilized in electronic books, magazines, and electronics catalogs.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The old units "mfd" and "mf" meant *microfarad* (μF); and the old units "mmfd", "mmf", "uuf", "μμf", "pfd" meant *picofarad* (pF); but they are rarely used any more.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Also, "Micromicrofarad" or "micro-microfarad" are obsolete units that are found in some older texts that is equivalent to *picofarad* (pF).
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can store electric energy when disconnected from its charging circuit, so it can be used like a temporary battery, or like other types of rechargeable energy storage system.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are commonly used in electronic devices to maintain power supply while batteries are being changed.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can facilitate conversion of kinetic energy of charged particles into electric energy and store it.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] There are tradeoffs between capacitors and batteries as storage devices.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Without external resistors or inductors, capacitors can generally release their stored energy in a very short time compared to batteries.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Conversely, batteries can hold a far greater charge per their size.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Conventional capacitors provide less than 360 joules per kilogram of specific energy, whereas a conventional alkaline battery has a density of 590 kJ/kg.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] There is an intermediate solution: supercapacitors, which can accept and deliver charge much faster than batteries, and tolerate many more charge and discharge cycles than rechargeable batteries.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] They are, however, 10 times larger than conventional batteries for a given charge.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] On the other hand, it has been shown that the amount of charge stored in the dielectric layer of the thin film capacitor can be equal to, or can even exceed, the amount of charge stored on its plates.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] In car audio systems, large capacitors store energy for the amplifier to use on demand.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Also, for a flash tube, a capacitor is used to hold the high voltage.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] In the 1930s, John Atanasoff applied the principle of energy storage in capacitors to construct dynamic digital memories for the first binary computers that used electron tubes for logic.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Pulsed power is used in many applications to increase the power intensity (watts) of a volume of energy (joules) by releasing that volume within a very short time.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Pulses in the nanosecond range and powers in the gigawatts are achievable.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Short pulses often require specially constructed, low-inductance, high-voltage capacitors that are often used in large groups (*capacitor banks*) to supply huge pulses of current for many pulsed power applications.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] These include electromagnetic forming, Marx generators, pulsed lasers (especially TEA lasers), pulse forming networks, radar, fusion research, and particle accelerators.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Large capacitor banks (reservoir) are used as energy sources for the exploding-bridgewire detonators or slapper detonators in nuclear weapons and other specialty weapons.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Experimental work is under way using banks of capacitors as power sources for electromagnetic armour and electromagnetic railguns and coilguns.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Reservoir capacitors are used in power supplies where they smooth the output of a full or half wave rectifier.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] They can also be used in charge pump circuits as the energy storage element in the generation of higher voltages than the input voltage.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are connected in parallel with the power circuits of most electronic devices and larger systems (such as factories) to shunt away and conceal current fluctuations from the primary power source to provide a "clean" power supply for signal or control circuits.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Audio equipment, for example, uses several capacitors in this way, to shunt away power line hum before it gets into the signal circuitry.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The capacitors act as a local reserve for the DC power source, and bypass AC currents from the power supply.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] This is used in car audio applications, when a stiffening capacitor compensates for the inductance and resistance of the leads to the lead–acid car battery.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] In electric power distribution, capacitors are used for power-factor correction.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Such capacitors often come as three capacitors connected as a three phase load.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Usually, the values of these capacitors are not given in farads but rather as a reactive power in volt-amperes reactive (var).
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The purpose is to counteract inductive loading from devices like electric motors and transmission lines to make the load appear to be mostly resistive.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Individual motor or lamp loads may have capacitors for power-factor correction, or larger sets of capacitors (usually with automatic switching devices) may be installed at a load center within a building or in a large utility substation.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Because capacitors pass AC but block DC signals (when charged up to the applied DC voltage), they are often used to separate the AC and DC components of a signal.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] This method is known as *AC coupling* or "capacitive coupling".
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Here, a large value of capacitance, whose value need not be accurately controlled, but whose reactance is small at the signal frequency, is employed.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] A decoupling capacitor is a capacitor used to protect one part of a circuit from the effect of another, for instance to suppress noise or transients.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Noise caused by other circuit elements is shunted through the capacitor, reducing the effect they have on the rest of the circuit.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] It is most commonly used between the power supply and ground.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] An alternative name is *bypass capacitor* as it is used to bypass the power supply or other high impedance component of a circuit.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Decoupling capacitors need not always be discrete components.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used in these applications may be built into a printed circuit board, between the various layers.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] These are often referred to as embedded capacitors.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The layers in the board contributing to the capacitive properties also function as power and ground planes, and have a dielectric in between them, enabling them to operate as a parallel plate capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] When an inductive circuit is opened, the current through the inductance collapses quickly, creating a large voltage across the open circuit of the switch or relay.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] If the inductance is large enough, the energy may generate a spark, causing the contact points to oxidize, deteriorate, or sometimes weld together, or destroying a solid-state switch.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] A snubber capacitor across the newly opened circuit creates a path for this impulse to bypass the contact points, thereby preserving their life; these were commonly found in contact breaker ignition systems, for instance.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Similarly, in smaller scale circuits, the spark may not be enough to damage the switch but may still radiate undesirable radio frequency interference (RFI), which a filter capacitor absorbs.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Snubber capacitors are usually employed with a low-value resistor in series, to dissipate energy and minimize RFI.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Such resistor-capacitor combinations are available in a single package.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are also used in parallel with interrupting units of a high-voltage circuit breaker to equally distribute the voltage between these units.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] In schematic diagrams, a capacitor used primarily for DC charge storage is often drawn vertically in circuit diagrams with the lower, more negative, plate drawn as an arc.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The straight plate indicates the positive terminal of the device, if it is polarized (see electrolytic capacitor).
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] In single phase squirrel cage motors, the primary winding within the motor housing is not capable of starting a rotational motion on the rotor, but is capable of sustaining one.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] To start the motor, a secondary "start" winding has a series non-polarized *starting capacitor* to introduce a lead in the sinusoidal current.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] When the secondary (start) winding is placed at an angle with respect to the primary (run) winding, a rotating electric field is created.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The force of the rotational field is not constant, but is sufficient to start the rotor spinning.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] When the rotor comes close to operating speed, a centrifugal switch (or current-sensitive relay in series with the main winding) disconnects the capacitor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The start capacitor is typically mounted to the side of the motor housing.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] These are called capacitor-start motors, that have relatively high starting torque.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Typically they can have up-to four times as much starting torque as a split-phase motor and are used on applications such as compressors, pressure washers and any small device requiring high starting torques.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitor-run induction motors have a permanently connected phase-shifting capacitor in series with a second winding.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The motor is much like a two-phase induction motor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Motor-starting capacitors are typically non-polarized electrolytic types, while running capacitors are conventional paper or plastic film dielectric types.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The energy stored in a capacitor can be used to represent information, either in binary form, as in DRAMs, or in analogue form, as in analog sampled filters and CCDs.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitors can be used in analog circuits as components of integrators or more complex filters and in negative feedback loop stabilization.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Signal processing circuits also use capacitors to integrate a current signal.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitors and inductors are applied together in tuned circuits to select information in particular frequency bands.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] For example, radio receivers rely on variable capacitors to tune the station frequency.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Speakers use passive analog crossovers, and analog equalizers use capacitors to select different audio bands.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The resonant frequency *f* of a tuned circuit is a function of the inductance (*L*) and capacitance (*C*) in series, and is given by: $f={\frac {1}{2\pi {\sqrt {LC}}}}$ where L is in henries and C is in farads.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors are designed to maintain a fixed physical structure.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] However, various factors can change the structure of the capacitor, and the resulting change in capacitance can be used to sense those factors.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitors with an exposed and porous dielectric can be used to measure humidity in air.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] ; as the fuel covers more of a pair of plates, the circuit capacitance increases.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Squeezing the dielectric can change a capacitor at a few tens of bar pressure sufficiently that it can be used as a pressure sensor.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] A selected, but otherwise standard, polymer dielectric capacitor, when immersed in a compatible gas or liquid, can work usefully as a very low cost pressure sensor up to many hundreds of bar.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitors with a flexible plate can be used to measure strain or pressure.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] use pressure-sensing diaphragms, which form a capacitor plate of an oscillator circuit.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] , where one plate is moved by air pressure, relative to the fixed position of the other plate.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] capacitors etched on a chip to measure the magnitude and direction of the acceleration vector.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] deployment, and in many other applications.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] musical instrument by moving their hand since this changes the effective capacitance between the user's hand and the antenna.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] are used on many consumer electronic products.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can possess spring-like qualities in an oscillator circuit.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] In the image example, a capacitor acts to influence the biasing voltage at the npn transistor's base.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The resistance values of the voltage-divider resistors and the capacitance value of the capacitor together control the oscillatory frequency.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] A light-emitting capacitor is made from a dielectric that uses phosphorescence to produce light.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] If one of the conductive plates is made with a transparent material, the light is visible.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Light-emitting capacitors are used in the construction of electroluminescent panels, for applications such as backlighting for laptop computers.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] In this case, the entire panel is a capacitor used for the purpose of generating light.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] The hazards posed by a capacitor are usually determined by the amount of energy stored, which can cause electrical burns or heart fibrillation.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Factors such as voltage and chassis material are of secondary consideration, which are more related to how easily a shock can be initiated rather than how much damage can occur.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Shocks over ten joules generally damage skin, and are considered hazardous.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Any capacitor that can store 50 joules or more is considered potentially lethal.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may retain a charge long after power is removed from a circuit; this charge can cause dangerous or fatal shocks or damage connected equipment.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] For example, the flash of a disposable camera has a photoflash capacitor that may contain over 15 joules of energy and be charged to over 300 volts.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Service procedures for electronic devices usually include instructions to discharge large or high-voltage capacitors.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors may have built-in discharge resistors to dissipate stored energy to a safe level within a few seconds after power is removed.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] High-voltage capacitors are stored with the terminals shorted, as protection from potentially dangerous voltages due to dielectric absorption or from transient voltages the capacitor may pick up from static charges or passing weather events.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Some old, large oil-filled paper or plastic film capacitors contain polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) which can leak into groundwater from landfills.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitors containing PCBs were labelled as containing "Askarel" and several other trade names.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] PCB-filled paper capacitors are found in pre-1975 fluorescent lamp ballasts, and other applications.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Such capacitors may be sealed in a metal can with ceramic feed-through connectors.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may catastrophically fail when subjected to voltages or currents beyond their rating, or in case of polarized capacitors, applied in a reverse polarity.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Failures may create arcing that heats and vaporizes the dielectric fluid, causing a build up of pressurized gas that may result in swelling, rupture, or an explosion.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors may have vents or similar mechanism to release of pressure in the event of failure.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used in RF or sustained high-current applications can overheat, especially in the center of the capacitor rolls.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used within high-energy capacitor banks can violently explode when a short in one capacitor causes sudden dumping of energy stored in the rest of the bank into the failing unit.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] High voltage vacuum capacitors can generate soft X-rays even during normal operation.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] Proper containment, fusing, and preventive maintenance can help to minimize these hazards.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] High-voltage capacitors may benefit from a pre-charge to limit in-rush currents at power-up of high voltage direct current (HVDC) circuits.
[src:energy-consumption/capacitor-p02] This extends the life of the component and may mitigate high-voltage hazards.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] A **carbon footprint** (or **greenhouse gas footprint**) is a calculated value or index that makes it possible to compare the total amount of greenhouse gases that an activity, product, company or country adds to the atmosphere.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Carbon footprints are usually reported in tonnes of emissions (CO2-equivalent) per unit of comparison.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Such units can be, for example, *tonnes CO2-eq per year*, *per kilogram of protein for consumption*, *per kilometer travelled*, *per piece of clothing* and so forth.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] A product's carbon footprint includes the emissions for the entire life cycle.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] These run from the production along the supply chain to its final consumption and disposal.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Similarly, an organization's carbon footprint includes the direct as well as the indirect emissions that it causes.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The Greenhouse Gas Protocol (for carbon accounting of organizations) calls these *Scope 1, 2 and 3 emissions*.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] There are several methodologies and online tools to calculate the carbon footprint.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] They depend on whether the focus is on a country, organization, product or individual person.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] For example, the carbon footprint of a product could help consumers decide which product to buy if they want to be climate aware.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] For climate change mitigation activities, the carbon footprint can help distinguish those economic activities with a high footprint from those with a low footprint.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] So the carbon footprint concept allows everyone to make comparisons between the climate impacts of individuals, products, companies and countries.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It also helps people devise strategies and priorities for reducing the carbon footprint.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The carbon dioxide equivalent (CO2eq) emissions per unit of comparison is a suitable way to express a carbon footprint.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This sums up all the greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It includes all greenhouse gases, not just carbon dioxide.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] And it looks at emissions from economic activities, events, organizations and services.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] In some definitions, only the carbon dioxide emissions are taken into account.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] These do not include other greenhouse gases, such as methane and nitrous oxide.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Various methods to calculate the carbon footprint exist, and these may differ somewhat for different entities.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] For organizations it is common practice to use the Greenhouse Gas Protocol.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It includes three carbon emission scopes.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Scope 1 refers to *direct* carbon emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Scope 2 and 3 refer to *indirect* carbon emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Scope 3 emissions are those indirect emissions that result from the activities of an organization but come from sources which they do not own or control.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] For countries it is common to use consumption-based emissions accounting to calculate their carbon footprint for a given year.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based accounting using input-output analysis backed by super-computing makes it possible to analyse global supply chains.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Countries also prepare national GHG inventories for the UNFCCC.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The GHG emissions listed in those national inventories are only from activities in the country itself.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This approach is called *territorial-based accounting* or *production-based accounting.* It does not take into account production of goods and services imported on behalf of residents.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] *Consumption-based accounting* does reflect emissions from goods and services imported from other countries.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based accounting is therefore more comprehensive.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This comprehensive carbon footprint reporting including Scope 3 emissions deals with gaps in current systems.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Countries' GHG inventories for the UNFCCC do not include international transport.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Comprehensive carbon footprint reporting looks at the final demand for emissions, to where the consumption of the goods and services takes place.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Scientists report carbon footprints in terms of equivalents of tonnes of CO2 emissions (CO2-equivalent).
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] They may report them per year, per person, per kilogram of protein, per kilometer travelled, and so on.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] In the definition of carbon footprint, some scientists include only CO2.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] But more commonly they include several of the notable greenhouse gases.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] They can compare various greenhouse gases by using carbon dioxide equivalents over a relevant time scale, like 100 years.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Some organizations use the term *greenhouse gas footprint* or *climate footprint* to emphasize that all greenhouse gases are included, not just carbon dioxide.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The Greenhouse Gas Protocol includes all of the most important greenhouse gases.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] In comparison, the IPCC definition of *carbon footprint* in 2022 covers only carbon dioxide.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] That publication included only carbon dioxide in the definition of carbon footprint.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It justified this with the argument that other greenhouse gases were more difficult to quantify.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This is because of their differing global warming potentials.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] They also stated that an inclusion of all greenhouse gases would make the carbon footprint indicator less practical.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] But there are disadvantages to this approach.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] One disadvantage of not including methane is that some products or sectors that have a high methane footprint such as livestock appear less harmful for the climate than they actually are.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The greenhouse gas protocol is a set of standards for tracking greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The standards divide emissions into three *scopes (S*cope 1, 2 and 3) within the value chain.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Greenhouse gas emissions caused directly by the organization such as by burning fossil fuels are referred to as S*cope 1*.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Emissions caused indirectly by an organization, such as by purchasing secondary energy sources like electricity, heat, cooling or steam are called *Scope 2*.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Lastly, indirect emissions associated with upstream or downstream processes are called *Scope 3*.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Direct or *Scope 1* carbon emissions come from sources on the site that is producing a product or delivering a service.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] An example for industry would be the emissions from burning a fuel on site.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] On the individual level, emissions from personal vehicles or gas-burning stoves are Scope 1.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Indirect carbon emissions are emissions from sources upstream or downstream from the process being studied.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] They are also known as *Scope 2* or *Scope 3* emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Scope 2 emissions are the indirect emissions related to purchasing electricity, heat, or steam used on site.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Examples of upstream carbon emissions include transportation of materials and fuels, any energy used outside of the production facility, and waste produced outside the production facility.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Examples of downstream carbon emissions include any end-of-life process or treatments, product and waste transportation, and emissions associated with selling the product.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The GHG Protocol says it is important to calculate upstream and downstream emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Scope 3 emissions are all other indirect emissions derived from the activities of an organization.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] But they are from sources they do not own or control.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The GHG Protocol's *Corporate Value Chain (Scope 3) Accounting and Reporting Standard* allows companies to assess their entire value chain emissions impact and identify where to focus reduction activities.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Scope 3 emission sources include emissions from suppliers and product users.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] These are also known as the *value chain*.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Transportation of goods, and other indirect emissions are also part of this scope.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] In 2022 about 30% of US companies reported Scope 3 emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The International Sustainability Standards Board is developing a recommendation to include Scope 3 emissions in all GHG reporting.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The current rise in global average temperature is more rapid than previous changes.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It is primarily caused by humans burning fossil fuels.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The increase in greenhouse gases in the atmosphere is also due to deforestation and agricultural and industrial practices.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The two most notable greenhouse gases are carbon dioxide and methane.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Greenhouse gas emissions, and hence humanity's carbon footprint, have been increasing during the 21st century.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The Paris Agreement aims to reduce greenhouse gas emissions enough to limit the rise in global temperature to no more than 1.5 °C above pre-industrial levels.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint concept makes comparisons between the climate impacts of individuals, products, companies and countries.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] A carbon footprint label on products could enable consumers to choose products with a lower carbon footprint if they want to help limit climate change.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] For meat products, as an example, such a label could make it clear that beef has a higher carbon footprint than chicken.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Understanding the size of an organization's carbon footprint makes it possible to devise a strategy to reduce it.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] For most businesses the vast majority of emissions do not come from activities on site, known as Scope 1, or from energy supplied to the organization, known as Scope 2, but from Scope 3 emissions, the extended upstream and downstream supply chain.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Therefore, ignoring Scope 3 emissions makes it impossible to detect all emissions of importance, which limits options for mitigation.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Large companies in sectors such as clothing or automobiles would need to examine more than 100,000 supply chain pathways to fully report their carbon footprints.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The importance of displacement of carbon emissions has been known for some years.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Scientists also call this carbon leakage.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The idea of a carbon footprint addresses concerns of carbon leakage which the Paris Agreement does not cover.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Carbon leakage occurs when importing countries outsource production to exporting countries.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The outsourcing countries are often rich countries while the exporters are often low-income countries.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Countries can make it appear that their GHG emissions are falling by moving "dirty" industries abroad, even if their emissions could be increasing when looked at from a consumption perspective.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Carbon leakage and related international trade have a range of environmental impacts.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] These include increased air pollution, water scarcity, biodiversity loss, raw material usage, and energy depletion.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Scholars have argued in favour of using both consumption-based and production-based accounting.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This helps establish shared producer and consumer responsibility.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Currently countries report on their annual GHG inventory to the UNFCCC based on their territorial emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This is known as the territorial-based or production-based approach.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Including consumption-based calculations in the UNFCCC reporting requirements would help close loopholes by addressing the challenge of carbon leakage.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The Paris Agreement currently does not require countries to include in their national totals GHG emissions associated with international transport.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] These emissions are reported separately.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] They are not subject to the limitation and reduction commitments of Annex 1 Parties under the Climate Convention and Kyoto Protocol.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint methodology includes GHG emissions associated with international transport, thereby assigning emissions caused by international trade to the importing country.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The calculation of the carbon footprint of a product, service or sector requires expert knowledge and careful examination of what is to be included.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Carbon footprints can be calculated at different scales.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] They can apply to whole countries, cities, neighborhoods and also sectors, companies and products.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Several free online carbon footprint calculators exist to calculate personal carbon footprints.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Software such as the "Scope 3 Evaluator" can help companies report emissions throughout their value chain.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The software tools can help consultants and researchers to model global sustainability footprints.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] In each situation there are a number of questions that need to be answered.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] These include which activities are linked to which emissions, and which proportion should be attributed to which company.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Software is essential for company management.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] But there is a need for new ways of enterprise resource planning to improve corporate sustainability performance.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] To achieve 95% carbon footprint coverage, it would be necessary to assess 12 million individual supply-chain contributions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This is based on analyzing 12 sectoral case studies.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The Scope 3 calculations can be made easier using input-output analysis.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This is a technique originally developed by Nobel Prize-winning economist Wassily Leontief.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based emission accounting traces the impacts of demand for goods and services along the global supply chain to the end-consumer.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It is also called consumption-based carbon accounting.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] In contrast, a *production-based approach* to calculating GHG emissions is not a carbon footprint analysis.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This approach is also called a *territorial-based approach.* The production-based approach includes only impacts physically produced in the country in question.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based accounting redistributes the emissions from production-based accounting.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It considers that emissions in another country are necessary for the home country's consumption bundle.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Consumer-based accounting is based on input-output analysis.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It is used at the highest levels for any economic research question related to environmental or social impacts.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Analysis of global supply chains is possible using consumption-based accounting with input-output analysis assisted by super-computing capacity.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Leontief created Input-output analysis (IO) to demonstrate the relationship between consumption and production in an economy.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It incorporates the entire supply chain.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It uses input-output tables from countries' national accounts.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It also uses international data such as UN Comtrade and Eurostat.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Input-output analysis has been extended globally to multi-regional input-output analysis (MRIO).
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Innovations and technology enabling the analysis of billions of supply chains made this possible.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Standards set by the United Nations underpin this analysis.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The analysis enables a *Structural Path Analysis.* This scans and ranks the top supply chain nodes and paths.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It conveniently lists hotspots for urgent action.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Input-output analysis has increased in popularity because of its ability to examine global value chains.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Life cycle assessment (LCA) is a methodology for assessing all environmental impacts associated with the life cycle of a commercial product, process, or service.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It is not limited to the greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It includes water pollution, air pollution, ecotoxicity and similar types of pollution.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Some widely recognized procedures for LCA are included in the ISO 14000 series of environmental management standards.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] A standard called ISO 14040:2006 provides the framework for conducting an LCA study.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] ISO 14060 family of standards provides further sophisticated tools.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Also the latest standard, ISO 14064:2018 has the right set of tools that will help reduce Carbon Emissions in Corporations.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] These are used to quantify, monitor, report and validate or verify GHG emissions and removals.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Greenhouse gas product life cycle assessments can also comply with specifications such as Publicly Available Specification (PAS) 2050 and the GHG Protocol Life Cycle Accounting and Reporting Standard.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] An advantage of LCA is the high level of detail that can be obtained on-site or by liaising with suppliers.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] However, LCA has been hampered by the artificial construction of a boundary after which no further impacts of upstream suppliers are considered.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This can introduce significant truncation errors.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] LCA has been combined with input-output analysis.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This enables on-site detailed knowledge to be incorporated.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] IO connects to global economic databases to incorporate the entire supply chain.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Critics argue that the original aim of promoting the personal carbon footprint concept was to shift responsibility away from corporations and institutions and on to personal lifestyle choices.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The fossil fuel company BP ran a large advertising campaign for the personal carbon footprint in 2004 which helped popularize this concept.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This strategy, employed by many major fossil fuel companies, has been criticized for trying to shift the blame for negative consequences of those industries on to individual choices.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Geoffrey Supran and Naomi Oreskes of Harvard University argue that concepts such as carbon footprints "hamstring us, and they put blinders on us, to the systemic nature of the climate crisis and the importance of taking collective action to address the problem".
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] While the focus on individual behaviour has shaped public discourse, scientific assessments emphasize that this approach alone is insufficient.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The IPCC notes that individual behavioural changes alone are insufficient to achieve deep emission reductions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Reducing emissions through behaviour is important, but eliminating combustion altogether through systemic change is critical to long-term climate goals.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] A focus on carbon footprints can lead people to ignore or even exacerbate other related environmental issues of concern.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] These include biodiversity loss, ecotoxicity, and habitat destruction.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It may not be easy to measure these other human impacts on the environment with a single indicator like the carbon footprint.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Consumers may think that the carbon footprint is a proxy for environmental impact.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] There can be trade-offs between reducing carbon footprint and environmental protection goals.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] One example is the use of biofuel, a renewable energy source that can reduce the carbon footprint of the energy supply but can also pose ecological challenges during its production.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This is because it is often produced in monocultures with ample use of fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Another example is offshore wind parks, which could have unintended impacts on marine ecosystems.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint analysis solely focuses on greenhouse gas emissions, unlike a life-cycle assessment which is much broader and looks at all environmental impacts.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Therefore, it is useful to stress in communication activities that the carbon footprint is just one in a family of indicators (e.g. ecological footprint, water footprint, land footprint, and material footprint), and should not be looked at in isolation.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] In fact, carbon footprint can be treated as one component of ecological footprint.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The "Sustainable Consumption and Production Hotspot Analysis Tool" (SCP-HAT) is a tool to place carbon footprint analysis into a wider perspective.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It includes a number of socio-economic and environmental indicators.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It offers calculations that are either consumption-based, following the carbon footprint approach, or production-based.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The database of the SCP-HAT tool is underpinned by input–output analysis.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This means it includes Scope 3 emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The IO methodology is also governed by UN standards.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It is based on input-output tables of countries' national accounts and international trade data such as UN Comtrade, and therefore it is comparable worldwide.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The term *carbon footprint* has been applied to limited calculations that do not include Scope 3 emissions or the entire supply chain.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This can lead to claims of misleading customers with regards to the real carbon footprints of companies or products.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Greenhouse gas emissions (GHG emissions) from human activities intensify the greenhouse effect which contributes to climate change.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Carbon dioxide (CO2) from burning fossil fuels (such as coal, oil, and natural gas) is the main cause of climate change.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The largest annual emissions are from China followed by the United States, which has higher emissions per capita.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The main producers fueling the emissions globally are large oil and gas companies.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Emissions from human activities have increased atmospheric carbon dioxide by about 50% over pre-industrial levels.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The growing levels of emissions have varied, but have been consistent among all greenhouse gases.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Over 60 billion tons were emitted in 2025, higher than any year before.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Total cumulative emissions from 1870 to 2022 were 703 GtC (2575 GtCO2), of which 484±20 GtC (1773±73 GtCO2) from fossil fuels and industry, and 219±60 GtC (802±220 GtCO2) from land use change.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Land-use change, such as deforestation, caused about 31% of cumulative emissions over 1870–2022, coal 32%, oil 24%, and gas 10%.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Carbon dioxide is the main greenhouse gas resulting from human activities.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It accounts for more than half of warming.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Methane (CH4) emissions have almost the same short-term impact.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Nitrous oxide (N2O) and fluorinated gases (F-gases) play a lesser role in comparison.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Emissions of carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide in 2023 were all higher than ever before.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The Carbon Trust has worked with UK manufacturers to produce "thousands of carbon footprint assessments".
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] As of 2014 the Carbon Trust state they have measured 28,000 certifiable product carbon footprints.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This NGO has also developed a labelling scheme which "supports informed consumer choices and business procurement decisions".
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Plant-based foods tend to have a lower carbon footprint than meat and dairy.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This holds true when comparing the footprint of foods in terms of their weight, protein content or calories.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The protein output of peas and beef provides an example.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Producing 100 grams of protein from peas emits just 0.4 kilograms of carbon dioxide equivalents (CO2eq).
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] To get the same amount of protein from beef, emissions would be nearly 90 times higher, at 35 kgCO2eq.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Only a small fraction of the carbon footprint of food comes from transport and packaging.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Most of it comes from processes on the farm, or from land use change.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This means the choice of what to eat has a larger potential to reduce carbon footprint than how far the food has traveled, or how much packaging it is wrapped in.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The IPCC Sixth Assessment Report found that global GHG emissions have continued to rise across all sectors.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The most rapid growth was in transport and industry.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] A key driver of global carbon emissions is affluence.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The IPCC noted that the wealthiest 10% in the world contribute between about one third to one half (36%–45%) of global GHG emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Researchers have previously found that affluence is the key driver of carbon emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It has a bigger impact than population growth.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] And it counters the effects of technological developments.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Continued economic growth mirrors the increasing trend in material extraction and GHG emissions**.** "Industrial emissions have been growing faster since 2000 than emissions in any other sector, driven by increased basic materials extraction and production," the IPCC said.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] There can be wide variations in emissions for transport of people.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] They include the length of the trip, the source of electricity in the local grid and the occupancy of public transport.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] In the case of driving the type of vehicle and number of passengers are factors.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Over short to medium distances, walking or cycling are nearly always the lowest carbon way to travel.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint of cycling one kilometer is usually in the range of 16 to 50 grams CO2eq per km.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] For moderate or long distances, trains nearly always have a lower carbon footprint than other options.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Carbon accounting, also called greenhouse gas accounting or GHG accounting, is a framework of methods to measure and track how much greenhouse gas (GHG) an organization emits.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It can also be used to track projects or actions to reduce emissions in sectors such as forestry or renewable energy.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Corporations, cities and other groups use these techniques to help limit climate change.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Organizations will often set an emissions baseline, create targets for reducing emissions, and track progress towards them.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The accounting methods enable them to do this in a more consistent and transparent manner.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The main reasons for GHG accounting are to address social responsibility concerns or meet legal requirements.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Public rankings of companies, financial due diligence and potential cost savings are other reasons.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] GHG accounting methods help investors better understand the climate risks of companies they invest in.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] They also help with net zero emission goals of corporations or communities.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Many governments around the world require various forms of reporting.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] There is some evidence that programs that require GHG accounting help to lower emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Markets for buying and selling carbon credits depend on accurate measurement of emissions and emission reductions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] These techniques can help to understand the impacts of specific products and services.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] They do this by quantifying their GHG emissions throughout their lifecycle (carbon footprint).
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] CO2 emissions of countries are typically measured on the basis of *production*.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This accounting method is sometimes referred to as *territorial emissions.* Countries use it when they report their emissions, and set domestic and international targets such as Nationally Determined Contributions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] *Consumption*-based emissions on the other hand are adjusted for trade.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] To calculate consumption-based emissions analysts have to track which goods are traded across the world.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Whenever a product is imported, all CO2 emissions that were emitted in the production of that product are included.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based emissions reflect the lifestyle choices of a country's citizens.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] According to the World Bank, the global average carbon footprint in 2014 was about 5 tonnes of CO2 per person, measured on a production basis.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The EU average for 2007 was about 13.8 tonnes CO2e per person.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] For the USA, Luxembourg and Australia it was over 25 tonnes CO2e per person.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] In 2017, the average for the USA was about 20 metric tonnes CO2e per person.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This is one of the highest per capita figures in the world.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The footprints per capita of countries in Africa and India were well below average.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Assuming a global population of around 9–10 billion by 2050, a carbon footprint of about 2–2.5 tonnes CO2e per capita is needed to stay within a 2 °C target.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] These carbon footprint calculations are based on a consumption-based approach using a Multi-Regional Input-Output (MRIO) database.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This database accounts for all greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions in the global supply chain and allocates them to the final consumer of the purchased commodities.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Efforts to reduce the carbon footprint of products, services, and organizations help limit climate change.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Such activities are called climate change mitigation.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Climate change mitigation, also called decarbonisation, is an action to limit the greenhouse gases in the atmosphere that cause climate change.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Climate change mitigation actions include conserving energy and replacing fossil fuels with clean energy sources.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Secondary mitigation strategies include changes to land use and removing carbon dioxide (CO2) from the atmosphere.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] 2022 assessments emphasize that global greenhouse gas emissions must peak before 2025 and decline by about 43% by 2030 to limit warming to 1.5 °C, requiring rapid transitions in energy, transport, and land-use systems.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Carbon offsetting can reduce a company's overall carbon footprint by providing it with a carbon credit.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] This compensates the company for carbon dioxide emissions by recognizing an equivalent reduction of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Reforestation, or restocking existing forests that have previously been depleted, is an example of carbon offsetting.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] A carbon footprint study can identify specific and critical areas for improvement.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It uses input-output analysis and scrutinizes the entire supply chain.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Such an analysis could be used to eliminate the supply chains with the highest greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The term *carbon footprint* was first used in a BBC vegetarian food magazine in 1999, though the broader concept of *ecological footprint*, which encompasses the carbon footprint, had been used since at least 1992, as also chronicled by journalist William Safire in the New York Times.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] In 2005, fossil fuel company BP hired the large advertising campaign Ogilvy to popularize the idea of a carbon footprint for individuals.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The campaign instructed people to calculate their personal footprints and provided ways for people to "go on a low-carbon diet".
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint is derived from the ecological footprint, which encompasses carbon emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint follows the logic of ecological footprint accounting, which tracks the resource use embodied in consumption, whether it is a product, an individual, a city, or a country.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] While in the ecological footprint, carbon emissions are translated into areas needed to absorb the carbon emissions, the carbon footprint on its own is expressed in the weight of carbon emissions per time unit.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] William Rees wrote the first academic publication about ecological footprints in 1992.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] Other related concepts from the 1990s are the "ecological backpack" and material input per unit of service (MIPS).
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The International Sustainability Standards Board (ISSB) aims to bring global, rigorous oversight to carbon footprint reporting.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It was formed out of the International Financial Reporting Standards.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It will require companies to report on their Scope 3 emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The ISSB has taken on board criticisms of other initiatives in its aims for universality.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It consolidates the Carbon Disclosure Standards Board, the Sustainability Accounting Standards Board and the Value Reporting Foundation.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It complements the Global Reporting Initiative.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] It is influenced by the Task Force on Climate-Related Financial Disclosures.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] As of early 2023, Great Britain and Nigeria were preparing to adopt these standards.
[src:energy-consumption/carbon-footprint] The *Expanded Total Equivalent Warming Impact* method has been used for an accurate evaluation of refrigerators emissions.
[src:energy-consumption/energy-consumption] From a societal and economic perspective, "energy consumption" often refers to the use of energy resources by human civilization to power homes, industries, transportation, and other activities.
[src:energy-consumption/energy-consumption] This typically involves drawing upon various primary energy sources, including fossil fuels (coal, oil, natural gas), nuclear power, and renewable sources (solar, wind, hydro, geothermal).
[src:energy-consumption/energy-consumption] The scale and patterns of this consumption have significant implications for environmental sustainability, economic development, and geopolitical stability.
[src:energy-consumption/energy-consumption] Analyzing trends in global and regional energy consumption helps policymakers and researchers understand resource availability, greenhouse gas emissions, and the potential for transitioning to more sustainable energy systems.
[src:energy-consumption/energy-consumption] In electrical engineering, "energy consumption" specifically refers to the amount of electrical energy utilized by a device, circuit, or system over a period of time.
[src:energy-consumption/energy-consumption] This is distinct from "power," which is the rate at which energy is consumed or transferred.
[src:energy-consumption/energy-consumption] While power is measured in watts (W) or kilowatts (kW), energy consumption is typically measured in watt-hours (Wh) or kilowatt-hours (kWh).
[src:energy-consumption/energy-consumption] Electrical engineers are deeply concerned with energy consumption for several critical reasons.
[src:energy-consumption/energy-consumption] First, it directly impacts operational costs for consumers and industries, as electricity bills are calculated based on kWh consumed.
[src:energy-consumption/energy-consumption] Second, energy consumption is inextricably linked to energy efficiency.
[src:energy-consumption/energy-consumption] An efficient electrical system or device converts a larger proportion of input electrical energy into its desired output (e.g., light, motion, computation) and minimizes conversion into undesirable forms, primarily heat.
[src:energy-consumption/energy-consumption] Understanding and optimizing energy consumption is therefore crucial for designing systems that are not only effective but also sustainable and cost-effective, leading to advancements in areas like power electronics, smart grids, and low-power integrated circuits.
[src:energy-consumption/energy-consumption] In the body, energy consumption is part of energy homeostasis.
[src:energy-consumption/energy-consumption] Energy consumption in the body is a product of the basal metabolic rate and the physical activity level.
